<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / International Company News: US subsidiary of Daiwa in SEC
settlement talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US subsidiary of Daiwa Securities, the Japanese broking house, confirmed
yesterday that it was negotiating a settlement with US government regulators
investigating the firm's role in attempts by Salomon Brothers to rig
Treasury bond auctions between 1989 and 1991.
Daiwa revealed that it was co-operating with the Securities and Exchange
Commission (SEC), the securities industry watchdog, in a separate
investigation into whether US subsidiaries of Japanese broking houses were
involved in reimbursing favoured customers for trading losses.
Last year, regulators in Japan temporarily suspended Daiwa for its loss
reimbursement practices.
The talks between the SEC and Daiwa revolve around the Japanese firm's
involvement in helping Salomon exceed government limits in a 1989 auction of
Treasury bills.
The complaint against Salomon filed by the SEC earlier this year described
how a dealer at another firm - now known to be Daiwa - handed over to
Salomon Dollars 3bn in Treasury bills that he had secretly bought at the
request of the US firm's chief bond trader.
</TEXT>
