<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / International Company News: Macmillan Bloedel warns of
losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MACMILLAN BLOEDEL, 49 per cent owned by Noranda Forest, Canada's biggest
forest products group, warned that British Columbia's five-week-old
pulp-and-paper strike could curtail its sawmill and logging operations.
This would have a heavy financial impact on Macmillan's third quarter, said
Mr Robert Findlay, president. Macmillan is a large timber exporter to the
US, Asia and Europe.
'The impact of the strike was not significant in the second quarter, but the
short-term outlook depends directly on the length of the strike,' he said.
Two unions representing 13,000 pulp-and-paper mill workers have shut down 19
British Columbia mills, including most of Macmillan's operations. Chips are
piling up at sawmills across British Columbia, threatening timber production
cuts.
Macmillan reported a first-half loss of CDollars 18.1m (USDollars 15m), or
20 cents a share, against a loss of CDollars 7.5m, or 13 cents, a year
earlier. Sales were CDollars 1.49bn against Dollars 1.4bn. Second-quarter
loss equalled 8 cents a share, against a loss of 13 cents a year earlier, on
sales of CDollars 775m against CDollars 728m.
Pulp prices improved but newsprint remained weak.
</TEXT>
