<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / UK Company News: National Home Loans reports losses of
Pounds 85.9m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL Home Loans, the mortgage lender that restructured Pounds 540m of
debt with its banks last month, yesterday reported pre-tax losses of Pounds
85.9m, much higher than expected.
The loss included a Pounds 79.4m loss provision, Pounds 52m of which related
to National Mortgage Bank, its banking subsidiary which is being run down
and is now held in NHL's books at nil value.
As expected, no dividend has been declared on ordinary shares and payment of
the convertible preference shares has been passed. The shares are priced at
2 1/4 p.
Mr Jonathan Perry, the executive chairman who took over in February, said
the group was now focused entirely on housing finance. Any chance of
recovering value for shareholders remained dependent on an improvement in
the housing market and in particular on cutting the number of accounts in
arrears. 'If we deal with the arrears problem successfully then we can see
the possibility of stemming losses and getting back into profits,' Mr Perry
said.
Some Pounds 20m of provisions reflected non-payment of current interest on
mortgages in arrears to National Home Loans Corporation. Staff are making
more than 30,000 telephone calls a month to try to reduce these arrears,
apparently with some success.
While many home owners were falling further behind in payments, the number
of hard-core accounts in arrears for more than three months has fallen by 10
per cent to 7,461 since its peak in February. Another Pounds 28m of
provisions covered additional specific and general provisions stemming from
continued deterioration in the housing market. There may be a need for
another increase in the general provision because of a further
deterioration.
The group also suffered a sharp fall in net interest income, from Pounds
25.7m to Pounds 6.4m.
</TEXT>
