<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / Accounts body plan attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Chartered Institute of Management Accountants has criticised the
Accounting Standards Board's proposals for an operating and financial review
in company accounts.
The Cima response follows the publication in April of a discussion draft of
the ASB review, which suggests that companies should be required to describe
their activities in detail.
Cima broadly supports the review, which echoes Canadian requirements and the
discussion and analysis in US company accounts.
It argues that the increases in management time, audit and other costs,
including the preparation of the review, are such that 'the board needs to
make a strong case for its provision'. It adds that the greater level of
disclosure should not place UK companies at a disadvantage in relation to
other European competitors.
Cima says that too much detail is required in the review and that might add
10 pages to the average annual report. The review should concentrate merely
on sales, profits and cashflow.
It suggests that the review might include a statement from leading lenders
to a company, giving their assessment of its financial needs and resources.
Cima says the board's suggestion that the review should be voluntary will
not work. To be effective, it should be enforced with an accounting standard
or be a requirement for a Stock Exchange listing.
Cima also argues that the review should be examined by auditors to ensure
that it is not inconsistent with UK company law and that accounts give a
true and fair view.
It suggests that aspects of the review should be included in the
recommendations of the Cadbury committee on financial aspects of corporate
governance.
</TEXT>
