FT  17 JUL 92 / Row over directorships averted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Adrian Cadbury, chairman of the Committee on the Financial Aspects of
Corporate Governance, has moved to avert a row over his position on whether
people should hold more than one non-executive directorship.
He said yesterday that there were advantages in holding more than one
outside directorship but non-executive directors who held too many posts
might not be able to meet the increased demands of the job.
Sir Adrian was speaking at a seminar on corporate governance sponsored by
the Institute of Chartered Secretaries and Administrators. He said he was
seeking to clarify remarks he made last month suggesting that individuals
could not be effective if they accepted more than one non-executive
directorship. His comments provoked a storm of protest from many
non-executive directors who hold multiple posts.
The Cadbury Committee recently issued a report urging a code of best
practice for corporate boards of directors which urges a greatly increased
role and responsibilities for non-executives.
Sir Adrian said yesterday he did not mean to imply in his earlier remarks
that it was advisable to hold only one directorship. 'There are advantages
in holding more than one outside directorship in terms of the exchange of
experience and of making the best of scarce resources,' he said. However,
holding too many posts could be a disadvantage.
According to Director magazine, published by the Institute of Directors,
some non-executives hold up to 10 different directorships.
Sir Adrian also urged companies to broaden the pool from which they selected
non-executive directors. Candidates might be divisional heads at leading
British corporations or come from the public sector.
</TEXT>
