<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / Business school wins fight for autonomy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANCHESTER Business School is to keep its separate identity and will
continue to operate with considerable autonomy from Manchester University,
its parent.
Arrangements finalised this week are seen as a shift of position by the
university after 14 private-sector members of the school's advisory board
resigned in May. They were protesting at plans to federate the graduate
school with other, mainly undergraduate, business studies sections in
Manchester.
Federation will proceed but the business school - which has an international
reputation that ranks its Master of Business Administration (MBA) degree
with those of Harvard in the US and Insead in France - will remain in its
buildings.
They include hotel-standard accommodation for students, who are all
experienced or senior executives and half of whom come from abroad.
'We need high-quality teaching and living facilities for competitive
purposes,' according to Professor Tony Cockerill, the school's deputy
director.
The business school will still be able to reinvest surpluses in improving
its facilities. This academic year it has made Pounds 350,000 on a Pounds
12m turnover.
With bookings full for MBA and senior executives' courses, the business
school expects similar profitability in the new academic year, which begins
next month.
The seriousness of the dispute over the school's future has prompted
Professor Martin Harris, who becomes the university's vice-chancellor next
month, to take the chair of a new interim management committee for the
school.
The committee will probably preside over the business school for a year
until an executive board is appointed with a majority of private-sector
members.
Mr Joe Dwek, chairman of Bodycote International and one of northern
England's most prominent business leaders, will be on the committee. Mr Dwek
has active links with the University of Manchester's Institute of Science
and Technology, which is putting its school of management into the new
federation.
Mr Edmund Gartside, of Shiloh, the Manchester textile company, will also
serve on the committee, along with Mr Tom Hinchliffe, a director of ICL, and
Mr Norman Quick, former chairman of Quicks, the car distributor.
No plans have been made to replace Professor Tom Cannon, who resigned as the
school's director a few days after the 14 board members. The job may rotate
among senior academics in the federation.
</TEXT>
