<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / Peace dividend at risk of draining away: The audit office
accuses Whitehall of costly defence spending errors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEFENCE ministers, contractors and civil servants are wasting tens of
millions of pounds of the peace dividend through mismanagement, political
interference in procurement decisions and foreign exchange errors, according
to an independent government report.
The National Audit Office's Statement on Major Defence Projects, published
today, lists errors that have cost tens of millions of pounds and are
leaving part of Britain's navy unable to defend itself.
The report comes less than a week after publication of the defence white
paper that detailed measures to make Britain's armed forces 'smaller but
better'. It is the more sensitive for being a first: until this year, its
contents were largely classified.
The report will make uncomfortable reading for Mr Malcolm McIntosh, the new
head of defence procurement, and his bosses, Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the defence
secretary, and Mr Jonathan Aitken, the minister for defence procurement. The
audit office is a government watchdog that examines the financial
performance of public bodies.
Perhaps the most serious of the audit office's accusations is that in 1987
Sir George Younger, then defence secretary, overruled Mr McIntosh's
predecessor, Sir Peter Levene, by insisting that a contract worth Pounds
130m was placed with the Swan Hunter shipyard on Tyneside.
Sir Peter had advised that that 'the prudent and economical course' was not
to accept the Swan Hunter bid to build the second of two auxiliary oiler
replenishment vessels. He wanted a competition for the contract.
The audit office says privately that the government decision to give the
order to Swan Hunter 'was political rather than economic': the yard had just
been sold by the government to its management.
The decision was one of a series of errors with the oiler contract that have
left the project almost three years behind schedule.
The oiler is an essential part of Britain's post-cold war naval defences,
supplying fuel, stores, maintenance and ammunition to ships at sea. Two have
been ordered by the MoD, the first from Harland and Wolff in Northern
Ireland, the other from Swan Hunter.
Both projects are now late, with Harland and Wolff so far behind schedule
that the ship has been sent to another yard, Cammell Laird, to be completed.
Exasperated at the delays, the MoD suspended payments to Harland and Wolff
in 1990 and 1991, but the audit office says: 'None of the sanctions imposed
by the department appears to have had a significant impact on the rate of
progress'. The original four-year timescale to completion has slipped to
almost seven years, with the first of the ships due to enter service at the
end of this year. The ships are also over budget: the original target price
for the contract was Pounds 122m a ship, and the MoD estimates that total
Harland and Wolff costs so far amount to Pounds 172m.
The audit office says the MoD had been 'over-ambitious' in awarding the
contract to Harland and Wolff, which had 'limited recent experience of
warship building'. Audit office officials say privately that Harland and
Wolff should never have been given the business because it had been late on
previous defence contracts.
The Swan Hunter deal is also criticised: the MoD decided to award the
contract too soon after Harland and Wolff had started work. The Northern
Ireland yard had not yet drawn up its construction plans and the MoD was
forced to pay up to Pounds 13m to Swan Hunter for another set of plans. It
had to accept a delay in the delivery date as a result.
Furthermore, says the audit office, neither ship will be able to defend
itself when launched over the next two years. The specification called for
the ships to be fitted with vertical-launch Sea Wolf missiles, developed by
British Aerospace and GEC-Marconi for protection against incoming missiles
and aircraft, and EH101 anti-submarine helicopters made by Westland with
Agusta of Italy. The EH101 is not expected to enter service until 1998, five
years late. While the Sea Wolf is ready, the ship cannot make use of them
until its command system becomes operational in 1996.
'These difficulties call into question the wisdom' of MoD procurement
policies that include new defence systems in a ship procurement contract,
the audit office says.
The MoD argues that it is only partly to blame for the delays in the oiler
construction projects. The department defended itself yesterday over the
oiler problems by saying contracts with suppliers were tightly drawn so that
contractors, not the ministry, would bear cost overruns.
But the audit office lists several examples where the department had to pay
more than the contracted price to Swan Hunter for items such as rewriting of
software.
The report concentrates on difficulties with the oiler contract but also
lists eight projects worth more than Pounds 250m that have had suffered cost
overruns of more than 5 per cent.
The mid-life update of the Tornado fighter aircraft and development of the
Type 23 frigate will have cost up to a third more than planned.
Another four projects will be more than 5 per cent cheaper than anticipated,
largely due to cuts in the size of orders.
Other losses include a Pounds 36,000 shortfall in foreign-exchange dealings
as a result of an omission in a contract with McDonnell-Douglas, the US
defence manufacturer.
The watchdog does not provide a total figure for the losses it has
identified because of inconsistencies in the way the figures are calculated
by the MoD and the Treasury. Nor did it give an overall view of how much a
typical project was delayed, this time blaming 'a lack of consistency in the
definition of in-service dates'. The army and air force, for example, had
different definitions for the entry dates of the British Aerospace Rapier
surface-to-air missile.
The audit office says such inconsistencies give 'a misleading impression
that equipment is universally in use by front-line forces and performing
fully to specification'.
The government is not likely to respond in detail to the report until
October, when parliament returns. Some responses should emerge when Mr
McIntosh gives evidence to the parliamentary Public Accounts Committee or
the Commons defence committee. When he does so depends on when he is called
by the committees.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
