<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / Single parents lose benefits battle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S system of income support, which can leave single parents better
off on the dole than working, is not a breach of European Community sex
discrimination laws, the European Court of Justice in Luxembourg ruled
yesterday.
Mrs Patricia Cresswell and Ms Sonia Jackson, supported by the Child Poverty
Action Group, had argued that Department of Social Security regulations made
it financially impossible for almost 1m mothers with young children to work.
Both mothers were challenging the Social Security Act 1986 which, unlike the
Supplementary Benefit Act it replaced, does not allow child-minding expenses
to be deducted from part-time earnings when assessing eligibility for
benefit.
Mrs Cresswell said she was Pounds 10 a week worse off by working part-time
as a graphic designer. She had to pay Pounds 25 a week for child-minding for
her six-year-old son but only the first Pounds 15 of her income was free
from DSS clawback of allowances.
The European Court ruled that the issue was not covered by EC directives on
equal treatment regarding access to work and social security.
Mrs Cresswell expressed disappointment at the ruling but said there was no
possibility of further appeal: 'If the government just gave us a little bit
of money to help us with our childcare costs we can take jobs and we are not
going to be claiming income support. That will benefit everybody.'
</TEXT>
