<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / Car output to be cut as sales fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CAR MARKET leader Ford is to cut production at its Halewood plant on
Merseyside for a month because of the continuing slump in new-car sales.
Peugeot Talbot is also to cut production by 7 per cent, with the loss of
about 100 jobs, after its 3,000 employees return from their summer break. It
says this is because of changes at its Ryton manufacturing plant near
Coventry in preparation for building a second model and not because of
economic factors.
Main rivals Vauxhall and Rover Group said yesterday they had no plans for
cutbacks. While Vauxhall forecast that it could achieve record production
this year, Rover warned that if August sales were significantly below the
400,000 for which the manufacturers hope, the industry could have no choice
but to cut output later in the year to prevent stocks building up.
The cutbacks were disclosed as the Society of Motor Manufacturers and
Traders and the Central Statistical Office jointly released statistics
showing that, in spite of the severe slump in new-car sales this year and
weakening exports, car production in the first six months, at 686,763, was
only 1.1 per cent lower than in the same period a year ago.
Total car production for June, at 129,219, was 3.31 per cent higher than in
June last year.
The statistics also show a sharp rise in commercial vehicle production for
the first half, up 24.72 per cent to 138,384 from 111,440, and up 49.3 per
cent in June, to 27,493 from 18,414. Unlike cars, the expansion in
commercial vehicle production was export driven, and largely because of the
start of production on Ford's new light-van ranges.
Ford is to abandon the night shift at Halewood for four weeks after the end
of the three-week summer shutdown. By doing so, it will lose output of
around 500 Escort and Orion models a day.
When two-shift working resumes, it will be on a four-day-week for a further
two weeks before production returns to normal five-day working.
Peugeot Talbot, denied its cutbacks were market linked. It had sold 5,000
more Peugeot 405s this year and seems to be heading for a record market
share.
The relatively high production figures for the first half reflect
preparations for an August sales bulge - expected to be 30,000 units higher
than last year's 370,000 - and predictions of an overall recovery for the
market in the second half. Both hopes now appear to be fading.
</TEXT>
