<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / Treasury plans to overhaul its model
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Treasury has commissioned research into consumer behaviour with a view
to improving its economic forecasts.
Two outside teams of researchers have been called in to overhaul the section
of the Treasury's computerised model of the economy that is linked to the
way people borrow and spend.
Warwick University and the National Institute of Economic and Social
Research are to examine these aspects of the model over the next year or so.
They will be taking into account both the financial deregulation of the
1980s and also the reduced demand for credit by many consumers during the
recession.
If the research is suc-cessful, the results will be translated into
mathematical equations and fed into the Treasury model - a vital tool used
in forecasting the economy.
The Treasury, like most private-sector forecasters, failed to forecast the
extent of the 1986-88 boom and of the recession.
In November 1990, the Treasury projected that there would be growth of 1 per
cent in 1991. In the event, the economy contracted by 2.4 per cent.
Behind the forecasters' failings has been lack of insight into spending by
consumers - which accounts for two thirds of gross domestic product.
Spending took off much more sharply than envisaged in the late 1980s, and
has fallen particularly steeply over the past two years, partly because of
the cost of servicing previous debts.
Under the new contracts, Warwick University's macro-economic modelling
bureau is to examine changes in credit constraints affecting consumers,
leaving the institute to look specifically at the housing market and the
links with borrowing.
The work is part of an effort by the Treasury to shift more of the
development of its model to outside researchers, rather than rely on its own
economists. The Treasury said the studies would look in detail at the new
information about consumer behaviour that has emerged in recent years.
</TEXT>
