<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / Winners of city renewal funds named: Pounds 2bn
private-sector top-up sought
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL HOWARD, the environment secretary, yesterday announced the 20
run-down urban areas which will share Pounds 750m of government City
Challenge funding over five years from 1993.
He said he expects the private sector to contribute more than Pounds 2bn in
partnership projects in the areas, taking the total investment to nearly
Pounds 3bn.
The 20 'winners', chosen in a competition judged by ministers on the basis
of bids put forward by all but three of the 57 urban programme authorities,
complement the 15 which gained funding under the first round of City
Challenge.
A majority of the 57 urban programme areas now have funding under the
scheme. But the losers are concerned because the Pounds 750m comes off
existing regeneration budgets.
Each winner gains Pounds 37.5m for a regeneration project in a particular
depressed area, in partnership with the private and voluntary sectors.
The 20 winning authorities are: Barnsley, Birmingham, Blackburn, Bolton,
Brent, Derby, Hackney, Hartlepool, Kensington and Chelsea, Kirklees,
Lambeth, Leicester, Newham, North Tyneside, Sandwell, Sefton, Stockton,
Sunderland, Walsall and Wigan.
In addition, Birmingham, Haringey, Plymouth and Stockton will gain 'task
forces' - small groups of civil servants charged with 'bringing residents in
their areas back into the economic mainstream.'
Virtually all of the 20 City Challenge authorities are Labour controlled,
and Mr Howard pointedly complimented them on their efforts. 'One of the
successes of City Challenge is the change it has wrought to the attitude of
councils controlled by Labour,' he said.
Mr Howard described the City Challenge programme as a 'revolution in urban
policy' which had 'transformed the way in which local authorities and their
partners have approached the task of urban regeneration'.
Privately, many Labour council leaders agree with him, recognising the
benefits of forging new links with business and voluntary bodies in their
areas.
But Mr David Blunkett, Labour's local government spokesman, objected to the
creaming of funds for City Challenge. He said funding for the urban
programme had been cut by Pounds 14.3m in the current financial year, and
the programme was now Pounds 121m less than it was in 1985-6.
'For the price of commissioning the Trident submarine . . . all those
bidding for City Challenge funds could have been granted the necessary
financial support to transform the inner-city areas and urban blight,' he
said.
</TEXT>
