<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / Gore calls for new generation of leaders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SENATOR Al Gore last night performed his first big duty as the Democratic
party's vice-presidential candidate: warming up the audience of party
delegates at Madison Square Garden for the man who last week picked him to
be his running mate.
Trading tales of hardship, Mr Gore paved the way for Governor Bill Clinton's
story of growing up poor in Arkansas with the tale of his son's almost fatal
car accident in Baltimore three years ago, according to a draft text of the
speech he had prepared for his acceptance of his party's vice-presidential
nomination.
'When you've seen your reflection in the empty stare of a boy waiting for a
second breath of life, you realise that we weren't put here on earth to look
out for our needs alone; we're part of something much larger than
ourselves,' he said.
Attacking President George Bush and Vice-President Dan Quayle for 'making
excuses for deadlock and decay', Mr Gore called for 'a new generation of
leadership for the United States of America to take over'.
'The American spirit isn't gone. But we vow here tonight that in November,
George Bush and Dan Quayle will be,' he said. 'They've had their chance and
they have failed. They have taxed the many to enrich the few. It is time for
them to go.'
Mr Gore hailed his running mate's achievements as governor of Arkansas in
shaking up one of the worst school systems in America, undertaking to reform
the welfare system and balancing 11 budgets.
He called, too, for a new effort to save the earth's environment - the cause
for which he has become best known during his Senate career.
'For generations we have believed we could abuse the earth because we
weren't really connected to it. But now we must face the truth. the task of
saving the earth's environment must and will become the central organising
principle of the post-cold war world.'
But he also appealed to those who have been supporting Mr Ross Perot not to
give up their fight for change.
