<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / Phone companies in US allowed to transmit TV
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A US government agency yesterday gave the go-ahead for telecommunications
companies to transmit television programmes to homes over their telephone
lines, a move which could eventually mean strong competition for the
monopolistic American cable television industry.
However, the ruling by the Federal Communications Commission, which oversees
the communications industry, is only a first step towards encouraging
competition in the potentially vast market for television-based home
information services.
First, the FCC has maintained a ban on the telephone companies' owning a
significant stake in a producer of the programmes transmitted through its
communications networks. Its ruling prevents the phone companies from owning
more than 5 per cent of a programmer, a slight relaxation from the previous
1 per cent limit.
Second, the telephone companies are in no position to offer immediate
transmission services, since video signals do not travel well on the copper
wire lines which currently connect nearly all American homes to the
telephone network.
Video signals require either coaxial cable, which is used by the cable
industry, or the new technology of fibre-optic cable, which can transmit
vast amounts of data of a high quality.
However, the telephone companies are expected to rewire much of their local
networks with fibre-optic cable over the next 20 years, and they have long
argued that the FCC move was vital to encourage them to make this
investment.
The cable television industry, which is under attack in Congress for the
sharply rising price of its service and fears the financial muscle of the
phone companies, opposed the FCC move.
However, the cable industry is also protected from competition under a 1984
act which prevents telephone groups from owning cable operators in areas
where the phone companies operate.
Mr Bob Levetown, vice-chairman of Bell Atlantic, a large regional phone
company serving part of the eastern seaboard, said the FCC move was 'an
important first step' but consumers would only realise 'the true benefits of
competition and choice when telephone companies have complete freedom to
provide video programming'. He urged Congress to remove the remaining entry
barriers.
</TEXT>
