<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / UN launches South Africa peace drive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL HOLMAN and AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE United Nations last night prepared to send an envoy to South Africa to
try to help end violence and bring about resumption of talks on the
country's constitutional future.
The Security Council gave the go-ahead to Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, the
secretary general, to send a special representative there on a fact-finding
mission.
The decision was taken unanimously by the 15-member body after a two-day
debate.
Mr Nelson Mandela, president of the African National Congress (ANC), urged
the UN to take such a step as an initial measure in a speech during the
debate. He said the special envoy should help the UN to decide on subsequent
action which, he said, should include 'continuous monitoring' of the
situation in South Africa.
The UN resolution condemned 'escalating violence' in black townships, in
particular the massacre of 43 people at Boipatong last month.
But it sought to find some middle ground between the ANC and President FW de
Klerk's government. It urged South African authorities to take immediate
steps to end the violence and bring those responsible to justice, while at
the same time appealing to all factions to avoid violence.
The resolution underlined the importance of all parties resuming talks on a
new constitution as soon as possible.
The secretary general's emissary to South Africa would recommend measures to
help bring an end to the country's violence and create conditions under
which negotiations towards a non-racial government can be resumed.
Earlier, Mr Pik Botha, South Africa's foreign minister, renewed his
government's call to the ANC to take part in talks aimed at ending political
violence. He also left the way open for a future UN observer mission to
South Africa.
Mr Botha, in an address broadcast live on South African television, told the
UN security council that the government was 'prepared to consider' a role
for the international community 'in an observer or other acceptable
capacity', working alongside a monitoring group which would include the ANC
and Chief Mangosuthtu Buthelezi's Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP).
Mr Botha did not elaborate on this proposal, hinted at earlier by President
de Klerk.
It seemed clear that the government would raise no objection to despatch at
this stage of a UN envoy on a fact-finding visit.
But political observers last night doubted that the stalemate on the
country's constitutional talks had yet been broken. Most observers doubt
that a formal resumption of negotiations can begin before a UN envoy has
reported back to the security council.
Mr Botha told the UN the government had nothing to gain from the violence
that led to last month's decision by the ANC to suspend talks.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
</PAGE>
