<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (28): Buy it for the
wall not the bottom line - Summer sees the opportunity to snap up the work
of tomorrow's top artists. But choose what you enjoy, or you may lose money
/ Alternative investments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BRITISH middle classes are not great art collectors. They prefer to
spend their surplus wealth on mortgages and school fees. But increasingly
they are tempted into picture buying, both to decorate their homes and
because they feel they could be investing in a bargain.
There is nothing easier than to spend up to Pounds 5,000 on a picture. But
how do you ensure that your purchase is a good buy?
No one should collect art purely for investment: if they do, they will
probably lose money. In the late 1980s, various sectors of British art - the
Newlyn School, the Scottish Colourists - were hyped by dealers to inflated
price levels. There are many people ruefully looking at a painting which has
lost both its creative and its financial appeal. You should buy art because
you enjoy a particular picture and want to live with it. That way you cannot
lose. It's an added bonus if it slowly appreciates in value.
There are some obvious rules for anyone concerned at the investment
potential of their chosen painting. It should be a good work by an
acknowledged artist and in perfect condition. Obviously a Royal Academician,
or a member of the Royal Society of Watercolourists, or of the Society of
Portrait Painters, comes with a seal of critical approval. Buying the work
of a contemporary artist keeps the tradition of privatepatronage alive and
makes for a more exciting commitment.
Perhaps the biggest array of art of a guaranteed quality is provided by the
Summer Show, which runs at the Royal Academy from early June until
mid-August. A judging panel has selected more than 1,700 works, some by
aspiring amateurs, from the 12,000 submitted, and leavened the display with
contributions from the RAs. Few of the paintings by the RAs are priced below
Pounds 5,000, but most others are modestly valued. The Summer Show is
criticised for its traditionalism, but it provides an unparalleled display
of mainstream British art.
It is a good idea to contact the artist of any work you admire and
commission a painting direct. This way you avoid paying the RA's (fairly
modest) commission.
One of the problems with buying art is that galleries, which often have a
precarious financial existence, can demand from unknown artists commissions
of up to 75 per cent in return for hanging their work, vastly inflating its
retail price.
Obviously it saves money to circumvent dealers, but owners of serious art
collections have invariably amassed them through working with a good dealer,
who offers experienced advice, and who will often agree to take back
paintings if a client gets bored with them.
If the Summer Show is the safe entree for the first-time buyer, anyone
wishing to be at the cutting edge of art will be better served at the annual
sale organised by the proselytising Contemporary Art Society, at Smiths in
London's Covent Garden, in October.
This presents itself as an art supermarket (it is actually sponsored by
Sainsbury's) and offers over 1,000 paintings all priced below Pounds 1,750.
Many are by established artists - Bridget Riley, Maggi Hambling and Craigie
Aitchison were on the walls last year - who like to hang alongside younger
artists. The aim is to encourage a new generation of informed collectors,
and, in prosperous times, queues form hours before the opening in the hunt
for bargains.
If you are feeling even more experimental, you should sound out the Degree
Shows of the leading art schools, such as the Royal College and St Martin's,
in London: the top dealers certainly have a prowl around.
These opportunities for the graduates to gain an instant reputation take
place in June. Thirty odd years ago, if your eye was right, you could have
acquired a Hockney for Pounds 20. The law of averages suggests that some of
the young artists parading their collages, videos, mobiles, and sculptures
will, in time, become RAs, great names in British art - and wonderful
investments. You may be surprised at the prices some of the students ask -
Pounds 1,000 plus is not unusual  - but haggling should secure a
satisfactory deal.
The success of the Degree Shows has encouraged other art colleges to pool
their resources for a London view, and 40 of them are participating in
'Fresh Art', to be held at the Business Centre in Islington from July 17. If
you are serious about art, rather than just looking for a picture to
decorate the living-room wall, you really should go to the college shows, to
take the pulse of the new generation.
Also at the Business Centre, the dealers in contemporary art gather once a
year to excite traditional customers and tempt in new buyers. Art 93 will be
held in January. Along with such established events as the Whitechapel Open,
where artists from London's East End, which numerically houses the largest
congregation of artists in the world, show the inspirations of the loft
culture, and the Bath Contemporary Art Fair in May, these are the main
gatherings events of the British contemporary art world.
Of course, the country is dotted with galleries. In certain parts of London
 -Portobello, Hackney, Barnes - they congregate in considerable numbers.
Glasgow and Edinburgh are well served to exploit the current high reputation
of the younger generation of Scottish artists.
The recession has hit galleries hard, and there have been many closures.
Artists are pursuing other avenues to sell their work - displays in
restaurants, offices, local craft fairs. These days you could find your
chosen work virtually anywhere.
The auction houses are also becoming more involved in selling contemporary
art at modest prices, and Sotheby's and Christie's in particular have sales
two or three times a year at which they expose established names to open
bidding. Obviously, in many cases this is buying art wholesale, avoiding the
dealers' mark-up.
Prices of art have stabilised or fallen in the past two years. Some forms,
especially watercolours, are undeservedly cheap compared with oils, and
there are bargains to be had in limited-edition prints - provided the
edition really is limited.
No one should rush into buying a painting, or a sculpture. Visit galleries
and fairs, study auctions and the art press, absorb yourself in the subject.
Make sure you really love the work you buy. And never buy just for
investment. Then there is a good chance that you will acquire a family
friend that could provide a windfall in the future.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXIV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
