<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (24): Supportive
columns - A guide to the information about trusts that is published each day
in the FT / Investment Trusts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOW CAN you use the Financial Times share price pages to help you choose an
investment trust, and to follow your trust once you have bought shares?
Almost two whole columns of the share listings pages are devoted to
investment trust share prices, with the trusts listed in alphabetical order.
One important point to note is that many trusts have more than one type of
share capital. The most common types are:
Capital shares. These have no fixed repayment value and pay no income. They
depend for their return on the trust managers growing the assets of the
trust.
Income shares. These get all the income of the trust, and have a very high
yield. But their repayment value may be low or virtually zero, so some
investors may simply be converting capital into income.
Warrants. These give the investors the entitlement to buy further shares at
a set price. The price of warrants can be highly volatile and they can
expire worthless; they also pay no income.
Zero-coupon preference shares. These pay no income but should be redeemed at
a much higher price in future. They thus offer steady capital growth and are
useful for people who do not pay capital gains tax.
If you are thinking of dabbling in any of these specialist classes of share,
or others such as stepped preference shares, you really need a stockbroker's
advice.
Once you have sorted out the class of shares you want, you can glean further
information from the share price pages. In most cases, we show the net asset
value (supplied by County NatWest Wood Mackenzie) and the discount or
premium on which shares trade.
This can be quite a good guide for general trusts - in theory, the wider the
discount the better. But care needs to be exercised. A wide discount may
reflect a poor management record. Any narrowing of the discount might be
counteracted, therefore, by poor asset growth. In addition, if the trust has
a large proportion of unquoted stocks, then the discount might reflect
investor suspicion of the real value of that unquoted element.
And the 'discounts' applied to capital shares of split trusts may be an
illusion, if the trust has zero-coupon shares with a steadily rising claim
on the asset base.
That said, it is obviously better to buy shares in an international general
investment trust on a 20 per cent than on a 10 per cent discount.
The listings also show the yield on each share. Again, caution is needed
before you assume that the highest yielding shares are the best. High yields
on income shares may reflect the prospect of capital loss; and on general
trust shares, a high historic yield may also reflect the expectation of a
dividend cut. One should also remember that yields in Britain are higher
than those in overseas markets, so geographical specialist trusts may not
offer much of an income.
Monday's listings show slightly different information, in particular the
dividends for the last year, the dates on which the dividends are paid, and
the last date on which the shares went ex-dividend.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-12668</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGQBQAD1FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920717
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (25): Three trusts
fail to reach their targets - A guide to the information about trusts that
is published each day in the FT / Investment Trusts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INVESTMENT TRUSTS have shown unexpected signs of life over the past three
months. Analysts had expected a slowdown in launches, while the big
management companies digested the money they had taken in at the end of the
last tax year, but it has not happened like that. Four companies went to the
market to raise funds via investment trusts.
The most ambitious offering was Thornton's, which in June raised Pounds
35.5m for its European Smaller Companies investment trust. The
country-specific fund management and stock-picking will be shared by
Thornton in London, BNP in France, and Dresdner in Germany, while asset
allocation will be determined using a newly constructed index.
Thornton chose a simple capital structure - just ordinary shares, with
warrants attached on a one-for-five basis. Henderson's European investment
trust offered 25 per cent of its share capital in zero-dividend preference
shares. Henderson's offer raised Pounds 17.3m, and chose blue-chip stocks
rather than smaller companies.
Edinburgh Fund Managers decided that the heavy falls on the Tokyo stock
exchange earlier this year meant the time was now right to launch a Japanese
general investment trust. EFM Japan raised Pounds 10m, with warrants
attached on a one-for-five basis.
None of these trusts raised its target. All were hit by gloom surrounding
the new issues market.
Kleinwort Benson offered a rather complicated trust to invest in the newly
developing market in secondhand endowment policies. It has a fixed life of
11 years, and the underlying investments are generally regarded as secure
enough for the trust's shares to be regarded as 'quasi-zeros'.
See also What's New? - Page 12
</TEXT>
