<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (23): Not quite as
portable as they seem - Group schemes / Personal Pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBBIE HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DRIVE towards group personal pensions has intensified over the past
year, with small to medium sized employers seeing this product as a cheaper
alternative to final-salary arrangements.
However, employees should beware the promise of portability without penalty
that these group plans claim to offer. All too often, employees who leave a
group personal pension face a hefty fine that reduces their fund by over 50
per cent.
At present, most of the UK's company pensions operate on a final-salary
basis. Under a typical scheme, your pension builds up at a rate of 1/60th of
your final salary for each year's service, up to an Inland Revenue limit of
40/60ths or two-thirds final salary, subject to a maximum of Pounds 50,000
where the 'earnings cap' applies.
Group personal pensions are money-purchase products, which means that
contributions are invested in a fund which is used to purchase an annuity at
retirement. Some companies have set up a different type of money-purchase
arrangement, known as a contracted-out money-purchase scheme (Comp), but
these are more complex and less popular.
At their most basic, group personal pensions are no more than a collection
of individual plans, although some providers reduce their charges due to
economies of scale. More generous plans also offer employer contributions,
death benefits and, less frequently, disability benefits. It all depends on
how much the employer is prepared to pay.
Group personal pensions have proved particularly popular among smaller
companies where the staff turnover is high. In theory, since each employee
has his or her own plan, this can be taken from job to job. But the claim of
portability without penalty is proving false.
The main problem is that company pension schemes are notoriously
incompatible. Unless the new company has an identical group personal
pension, the employee may be forced to abandon the original plan in order to
benefit from employer contributions and the other benefits associated with
the main company scheme.
So what happens to the existing plan? Any reduced charges that applied to
the group personal pension will not apply once the employee leaves. If the
employee joins the new employer's final-salary scheme, under Inland Revenue
rules it is not possible to maintain the personal pension plan (unless there
are additional self-employed earnings on which to base the contributions).
The plan can be made 'paid up', which means that no further contributions
are added and the existing fund continues to grow until the individual
retires.
This may sound fine, but invariably the pension provider will impose a
severe penalty if the contributions stop. This reflects the high up-front
charges that are incurred in sales of most personal pensions, including the
payment of commission to the adviser.
If you want to join the new employer's scheme, you could transfer-in your
personal pension fund. Unfortunately transfers, particularly in the early
years of a plan, reflect the hefty penalties associated with paid-up
policies. Typically, after two years, an employee is likely to get back just
50 per cent of the voluntary premiums paid in. (The appropriate rights fund
secured by the rebate of Serps contributions is treated less harshly.)
Some life offices have reduced the impact of capital units on their personal
pensions. These units, which are bought with contributions in the early
years of a plan, attract very heavy charges. Scottish Provident got rid of
its capital units altogether, and imposes no penalty on transfers. There is
still a deduction to cover up-front costs, but the transfer value is about
70 per cent of contributions paid, instead of the 40 per cent more typically
available where capital units are applied.
If you want to join the company scheme, one way of dealing with the personal
pension is to switch the fund into a free-standing additional voluntary
contribution (FSAVC) contract. FSAVCs are used to top up company schemes,
where the company pension is expected to fall short of the Inland Revenue
maximum.
But Peter Timberlake, marketing manager at Legal &amp; General, warned:
'Officially, the FSAVC is a new contract, and the conversion, even if it is
with the same provider, could incur fresh up-front commission for the
salesman or adviser.' Since there is no industry standard on this, it is up
to the individual to negotiate with the adviser to reduce the impact of
commission.
Unfortunately, even if the switch to an FSAVC can be achieved at little
cost, few young people with heavy mortgage commitments can afford to pay
both the occupational pension scheme contributions and to maintain the FSAVC
premiums. If the FSAVC premiums are reduced, once again a charge probably
will be incurred.
The same problem can arise where the employee leaves to become
self-employed. If the salesman and provider regard the switch in employment
status as an excuse to set up a new policy, full up-front commission will be
paid. Further problems arise where the employer previously made a
contribution. Unless the individual can afford to maintain the total
contribution level, the provider is likely to regard this as a drop in
premium and impose a charge accordingly.
Clearly, there seem to be portability problems associated with any change of
employment. The cost of switching to an FSAVC or self-employed contract is
likely to be every bit as expensive as making the plan paid-up or taking a
transfer to an occupational scheme. Whichever way you turn, you are caught
in a vicious circle that the pensions industry seems at pains to ignore.
If you are offered membership of a group personal pension scheme, check at
the outset what will happen to your fund if you change jobs. Some providers
may be more sympathetic to the transfer issue than others, particularly
those which operate on a non-commission or low-commission basis.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
