<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (22): Job changers
may lose a few years - Transfers / Personal Pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBBIE HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RECENT CONCERN over mis-selling of personal pensions for transfers from
occupational schemes has highlighted the plight of thousands of employees
who change jobs every year, little realising that each move can jeopardise
the value of their pension fund.
Those who have been in a company pension scheme for less than two years are
entitled to a cash refund of contributions, less a deduction for tax and
back-payments to the state earnings-related pension scheme (Serps).
After two years, you can leave the pension benefit in the former employer's
scheme or take a transfer value to the new employer's scheme or to an Inland
Revenue-approved private individual plan such as a personal pension or a
Section 32 buy-out bond (introduced under Section 32 of the Finance Act of
1981). Each option has its merits and drawbacks, and should be analysed
carefully in the light of individual circumstances.
The first option is to take a deferred pension - that is, to leave leave the
benefits in the old scheme until retirement. By law, schemes must pay
limited price indexation (LPI) of 5 per cent a year (or retail prices, if
less) on benefits in excess of the guaranteed minimum pension (GMP). The GMP
is the element of an occupational scheme that replaces the Serps pension.
While LPI, at a maximum of 5 per cent, represents an improvement in the law,
many would argue that it does not go far enough, given the fact that average
earnings inflation historically is about 8 per cent.
Larger schemes may award higher increases, often on a regular discretionary
basis. Schemes may also offer good death benefits and pensions for widows
and dependants. If some or all of these features are present, the
job-changer's best bet is likely to be a deferred pension.
Due to pending legal changes, there are other factors that could affect the
value of the deferred pension or transfer value. These include the
application of LPI to pensions in payment, the retrospective application of
equal pension benefits for men and women, and the uses of any pension scheme
surplus. Employees or their advisers certainly should consider these factors
before taking the decision to transfer out; but, according to Ian Sigston,
director of technical research at Noble Lowndes &amp; Partners, it is unwise to
attempt to 'double guess' which way the legislation will go and to delay
making an important decision.
The second main option - transferring to the new employer's scheme - often
leaves the employee feeling cheated. Before looking at this process, it is
important to understand how transfer values are calculated.
Most company pensions in Britain operate on a final-salary basis. Under a
typical scheme, the pension builds up at a rate of 1/60th of final salary
for each year's service. After 40 years' scheme membership, the employee
should qualify for the maximum pension permitted by the Inland Revenue of
40/60ths or two-thirds final salary. Employees caught by the 'earnings cap'
are further restricted to a maximum pension of Pounds 50,000 for the current
tax year. Employees usually pay contributions to their company schemes of 5
or 6 per cent per annum, while the employer's contribution will vary
according to age.
There are two schemes involved in an inter-company transfer - the ceding
scheme, and the receiving scheme. A typical transfer might reduce 10 'years'
in the old scheme to just five in the new scheme.
This is because the ceding scheme actuary turns the accrued number of
'years' into a cash value based on the value of the deferred pension plus
any increases to retirement. Due to the 5 per cent annual LPI cap on
deferred pensions, this immediately limits the growth assumption to less
than average earnings.
The receiving scheme actuary then calculates the number of 'years' this
transfer value will buy in the new employer's scheme, taking into account
any increases in salary to retirement and the level of benefits offered by
the scheme. Clearly, a higher salary and better pension scheme benefits will
'cost' more, and so reduce the number of years the transfer buys.
Only when the above options have been considered and found wanting should
the employee consider a transfer to a private plan. There are two options
here, namely a personal pension or Section 32 buy-out bond. The bulk of
current transfers to date have been to personal pensions, but there are
cases where a buy-out bond may be preferable.
Personal pensions are available from life offices, unit trust groups, banks
and friendly societies. Section 32 buy-out bonds are only available from
about 18 life offices. Both products operate on a money-purchase basis. This
means that your fund builds up to purchase an annuity at retirement. There
is no final-salary link, which makes it notoriously difficult to compare
company scheme benefits with these products.
While both products invest the transfer on your behalf, in order to provide
a fund at retirement to purchase an annuity, there are important
differences. For example, the buy-out bond can only accept the transfer
value, whereas it is possible to pay regular or additional single premiums
into a personal pension. Furthermore, the buy-out bond cannot be used to
contract out of Serps and is more restrictive in terms of retirement date
and investment scope.
However, the buy-out bond does offer important guarantees by retaining the
GMP, and for this reason the merits of this product should always be
considered alongside a personal pension for transfer purposes.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIX
</PAGE>
