<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (19): Check your
Serps position every year - Opting out / Personal Pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ERIC SHORT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EMPLOYEES WHO are relying on just themselves and the state for their pension
must decide how much they will do for themselves and how far they will rely
on the state.
All will receive the basic state pension. If they do nothing else, then by
default they are also in the state earnings-related pension scheme (Serps) -
the second tier of the state pension scheme.
But they have the choice of opting out of Serps, known as 'contracting-out',
and making their own provision through an appropriate personal pension.
With the general election over, some of the uncertainty about the future of
pensions has been removed. Employees can make the choice as to whether or
not to opt out of Serps with certainty, at least for the current financial
year. The choice depends on whether the employee considers that a personal
pension will provide a greater pension than Serps at the state pension age -
65 for men and 60 for women - for the particular year's contribution. It is
not an easy comparison.
The Serps pension for a year, say 1992-93, is a certain fraction of the
employee's earnings for that year between the lower earnings limit
(currently Pounds 2,808 a year) and the upper earnings limit (Pounds
21,060). This amount is revalued each year in line with national average
earnings until the employee retires.
In contrast, if an employee opts out of Serps, the contribution paid into
the personal pension would be 8.46 per cent of earnings between the lower
and upper earnings limits consisting of:
Employee's contracted-out rebate           2.00%
Basic tax relief on this rebate            0.66%
Employer's contracted-out rebate           3.80%
Incentive contribution                     2.00%
TOTAL                                      8.46%
Employees do not receive any tax relief if they remain in Serps. The
incentive contribution applies to all employees who have not been
contracted-out during the previous two years. It is paid from the National
Insurance fund. This contribution, less expenses, is invested in an
appropriate personal pension from a life company, and the accumulated sum at
state pension age used to buy a pension. So the longer the time to pension
age, the greater the accumulated sum, and thus the greater the ultimate
pension.
So, under the present regime, the younger the employee the greater the
pension secured from an appropriate personal pension, compared with the
pension from Serps which is virtually fixed in relation to the employee's
earnings.
Employees can obtain an individual benefit illustration, prepared under the
rules of Lautro (the self-regulatory body for the life insurance industry),
which compares the Serps benefit with that on a personal pension. The Lautro
rules, for once, are realistic for these illustrations, and employees can
make their choice on appropriate figures. A rule of thumb used by certain
life companies is that it is favourable for men up to age 45 and women up to
age 37 to contract-out of Serps with a personal pension.
Employees should check each year whether it is still advantageous, because
conditions are changing, and a different set of criteria will apply for
future years.
In April 1993, the rebate on National Insurance contributions is reduced to
4.8 per cent of earnings between the lower and upper limits - 1.8 per cent
for employees, and 3 per cent for employers.
In addition, the incentive payment, which was originally intended to cease
next April, will continue to be paid at the reduced rate of 1 per cent to
all employees aged 30 or more.
This in itself alters the equation, and the pivotal ages for contracting-out
will be a year or two lower than at present. These criteria, taken at face
value, would mean that employees presently contracted out through personal
pensions, who will have reached or passed the pivotal age by next April,
should seriously consider going back into Serps.
But the changes carry deeper implications, particularly the 1 per cent
incentive payment. It is widely interpreted that this payment heralds the
introduction of age-related rebates - that is, the level of rebate will
increase with the age of employees, to reflect the rising cost, with age of
matching pensions provided by Serps. If an age-related rebate system is
introduced, then there may not be any advantage in returning to Serps
whatever one's age. So employees should delay any decision until the
situation is clarified.
However, those relying on Serps, or its contracted-out equivalent, will find
that their ultimate pension will still fall well short of expectations,
particularly the higher paid. They need to top-up with personal pensions,
whether or not they are in Serps.
This message appears to be getting through. The Prudential group reports
that nearly three-quarters of employees who have contracted-out through
personal pensions have made additional provision.
Contribution rates are related to age:
Age                    Percentage of
                        net relevant
                            earnings
Up to 35                       17.5%
36-45                          20.0%
46-50                          25.0%
51-55                          30.0%
56-60                          35.0%
61-74                          40.0%
High earners, however, are restricted as to the ultimate amount of
contribution which they can make by the ceiling on their earnings - known as
'the cap'. This is currently Pounds 75,000. They can only relate their
contributions to personal pensions up to this limit. But this is the only
restriction imposed on personal pensions.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVII
