<DOCNO>FT923-12674</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGQBQADVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920717
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (20): With-profits
plans are the most secure - Choosing one / Personal Pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARBARA ELLIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PROCESS of choosing a personal pension plan starts with a calculation of
how much can be invested.
As background and a stark warning, the DSS will provide a forecast of how
much is due under the state retirement scheme, based on contributions
records.
Requests for this information must be made on form BR19, available from
local DSS offices.
Inland Revenue limits, scaled by age, currently allow between 17.5 per cent
(at ages under 35) and 40 per cent (between 61 and 74) of annual earnings to
be invested in a personal pension qualifying for highest rate relief.
Payments can be made and tax relief claimed up to six years after the
earnings are received.
There are four main types of personal pension:
With-profits plans, where the money is invested in gilts and property, as
well as shares, with the proportions chosen by the insurance company's
investment managers.
'With-profits' means that, each year, a share of the investment profits is
added to the policy for keeps. When the policy matures, a further terminal
bonus is usually also paid.
Unit-linked plans, where the money is invested in unitised funds chosen by
the investor from the range offered by the pension provider.
There are no bonuses: the value of the plan depends entirely on the unit
prices of the funds. So a stock market crash will severely damage a
unit-linked pension. Holders of unit-linked plans maturing in October 1987
found they were forced to postpone retirement by the 30 per cent drop in
plan values. Unit-linked pension policies usually allow holders to defer
cashing in, but legally the deferment cannot extend past the policyholder's
75th birthday.
Self-invested pensions, where an insurance company supplies the basic policy
and administrative services, while investors themselves, or managers of
their choice, select the investments without being limited to funds run by
the company.
Cash or deposit-based pensions, where interest rolls up gross.
Broadly speaking, with-profits plans are the most secure, though there have
been cuts in bonus rates and warnings of more to come.
Unit-linked and self-invested plans are riskier, and probably not suitable
for anyone within less than 10 years of retirement.
Cash-based plans do not have the long-term growth potential of stock market
investments, and tend to be a relatively short-term option for people close
to retirement.
Unit-linked plans now often have a facility for holders to switch into cash
two years before retirement, so as to avoid last-minute market plunges.
Most pension plans take either regular or single premiums, setting a variety
of minimum payment levels. A significant difference is that much higher
commission is charged on regular premiums than on single payments.
The retirement date written into the pension plan also influences commission
charges, which rise as the term increases. It is cheaper to set an early
retirement date, say 50, and then defer it if necessary, as this can be done
without the penalties imposed if retirement takes place before the date
specified.
Having chosen a basic type of plan, or perhaps a combination, the next move
is to find a pension provider with good investment performance and low
overall costs.
As commission is such a major component in costs, especially in the early
years of a plan, the most satisfactory way of buying a personal pension is
to go through a specialised adviser, who will charge a fee for advice and
rebate any commission in full.
Beware of advisers offering to rebate 'full Lautro commission'. This means
they will pocket a sizeable chunk of the commission, rebating only the
amount set out in the Lautro maximum commissions agreement scrapped three
years ago, since when commissions have rocketed.
Recently, the second annual commission survey by the regulator Lautro showed
that, in 1991, on average, independent advisers were receiving 23 per cent
more than the level set by the maximum commissions agreement for 10-year
pensions, and 26 per cent above for 25-year pensions policies.
Tied agents selling 10- and 25-year pensions were getting 44 per cent and 40
per cent more respectively than under the maximum commissions agreement.
This hefty bite out of the initial investment is not the only reason for
avoiding tied agents in the pension field. Another is that they can only
advise on or recommend the investments provided by the company to which they
are tied, instead of scanning the whole range on offer as independents are
supposed to do.
Assessment of future investment performance and costs is really a matter of
guesswork, based on past records.
The projections put out by the companies themselves are no help here, as
they are required to use standard growth assumptions and an industry-wide
average for expenses.
Recent research by the Securities and Investments Board showed what this
would mean to investors. Although companies' expanses knock anything from 6p
to 40p in the pound off pay-outs, the average to be used in projections is
14p. So some companies are vastly understating their charges.
One of the most reliable sources of comparative information about company
charges is a table derived from returns filed by life companies to the
Department of Trade and Industry. This was published in a simplified form in
the Weekend FT on February 22 this year.
The table shows an initial expense ratio, expressing the amount a company
spends on starting up a policy as a proportion of the first year's premiums,
and a renewal ratio, setting the running costs against the annual premium.
The sixty-one companies covered in the last table ranged from Equitable
Life, a company paying no commission, with an initial expense ratio of 24.1
and a renewal expense ratio of 4.57, to NEL Assurance with an initial
expense ratio of 307.65 and a renewal ratio of 2.39.
For past performance records of with-profits and unit-linked policies, one
of the most authoritative sources is Money Management, a monthly sister
publication to the Financial Times, which publishes annual rankings of past
investment performance over different periods.
Any statistics rehashed by a company and presented in a favourable light
should be rechecked at source.
As a rough guide, it is worth remembering that a company proud of 'top
quartile' performance has probably never made it into the top ten.
</TEXT>
