<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (20): Threatened by
their own success - Government concessions, spectacular marketing and
anxiety about the safety of employers' schemes have helped to boost the
sales of personal pensions. But the climate is changing / Personal Pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS A product, personal pensions have been spectacularly more successful than
even their designers can have hoped.
The latest figures from the Department of Social Security showed that 4.6m
people held personal pensions, and the indications are that the number is
still rising.
For the life insurance industry, the main purveyor of the product, they have
proved a boon during the lean years of the recession, with single-premium
pensions business having risen by 45 per cent in the year to March 31.
In explaining this spectacular success, analysts point to two key factors.
The first is the introduction of government incentives, designed to
encourage young people to opt out of the State Earnings-related Pension
Scheme (Serps). 'These products have been sold to young people on the basis
that the government is offering you a bribe to opt out,' said Mr Stewart
Ritchie, pensions manager at Scottish Equitable.
Indeed, the DSS's forecast of the number who would take up the initial offer
of a personal pension, 500,000 at the most, was based on an assumption that
no incentive would be offered at all.
The second factor is the spectacular marketing effort launched by the life
insurers themselves. This has been given a late boost by the collapse of
occupational pension schemes controlled by the late Mr Robert Maxwell with
over Pounds 400m of members' assets apparently stolen.
This combination of give-aways from the National Insurance fund,
enthusiastic sales agents and anxiety about the safety of employer-run
schemes in general helped to boost personal pension sales to Pounds 5.9bn in
the year to March 31.
But recently the government has proposed that, from next April, there should
be less generous incentives, limited to those over 30 years of age; while
the antics of some over-enthusiastic pensions sales agents has turned a
harsh spotlight on some of their sales claims, with consumer advocates
singling out the product for special criticism. So the question facing the
industry is whether the growth seen in the past four years is likely to
continue; and, if not, how will the pensions industry adapt?
'It will still be a very strong area of growth, but not as strong as it has
been,' predicts Mr Brian Sharp, secretary to the Association of British
Insurers Life Insurance Council.
Before personal pensions were launched, it was estimated that 10m employed
people were not covered by any occupational scheme, and it was at this pool
that the initial sales pitch was aimed.
'Now that group is fairly saturated,' said Mr Sharp. New business, he added,
had come largely from existing personal pension holders topping up their
policies, or from people changing jobs who had opted to place the transfer
value from a previous pension scheme into a personal pension.
It is these new sources of growth that have caused most anxiety among
consumer advocates and regulators, who are concerned about the wanton sale
of personal pensions to those people for whom they are clearly
inappropriate.
A protected-rights personal pension may well be a less attractive option for
a job-changer, and should only be considered after the merits of both the
former and future employers' schemes have been reviewed in detail. Those
leaving with a redundancy payment, and who remain unemployed, cannot take
advantage of the tax incentives of personal pensions.
Helena Wiesner, a consumer affairs consultant, who recently completed a
study of retail financial products for the Office of Fair Trading, expressed
concern about sales tactics. She cited figures from the Department of Social
Services for the 1988-89 tax year, showing that personal pensions were sold
to 63,000 women who had no earnings at all and were therefore ineligible for
tax incentives.
Lautro, the self-regulatory body for the life insurance industry, in
recording a 77 per cent increase in complaints last year, singled out the
sale of personal pensions for particular concern. It mentioned several cases
of commission-based sales agents who had encouraged individuals to switch
out of perfectly good occupational pension schemes into less desirable
personal pensions.
Like life insurance, personal pension schemes are frequently sold by sales
agents whose salary is dependent on the number of policies they sell. And,
like life insurance, sales procedures are subject to the same rules of
opaque disclosure, which make it difficult for consumers to learn exactly
what they are paying for. The industry faces the danger that dubious sales
tactics from a number of agents will cause their general lack of credibility
to rub off on the product as well.
Meanwhile, the industry must face up to somewhat less generous incentives in
future years. The cut in incentives, announced earlier this year, follows
widespread criticism that the incentives cost Pounds 5.9bn more than could
be saved from the National Insurance fund.
The lower rebate from next April, together with the reduced incentives, will
have the effect of encouraging people to opt back into Serps roughly five
years earlier than under the existing rebate. While actuaries' calculations
about the exact break-even age vary, the consensus is that men in their
mid-forties and women in their late thirties have more to gain by opting
back into Serps.
Meanwhile, the personal pensions industry remains uncertain about whether it
can count on the existence of incentive payments at all indefinitely. Both
Labour and the Liberal Democrats are pledged to end what both have described
as a bribe.
Furthermore, the Tory government's own intentions remain uncertain. While it
is committed in principle to encouraging individuals to opt out of the
National Insurance scheme, the method may well change. Indeed, the former
social security secretary, Mr Tony Newton, in announcing the new rebates for
the five-year period beginning next April, caused a stir when he said the
government would look into age-related rebates.
Larger contributions are required to a pension scheme as the member becomes
older. Thus, the incentives offered to young people opting for personal
pensions are larger than the contributions they would need to make if they
remained in the state system. By the time people reach their mid-forties,
the contributions required to a personal pension are far larger to obtain
the same benefits offered by Serps, and they are advised to opt back in.
The insurance industry has largely opposed age-related rebates, because they
would offer too little incentive to young people to opt out of the state
scheme, and older individuals are more likely to remain with their existing
arrangements.
However, Mr Ron Spill, pensions manager at Legal and General, a leading
provider of personal pensions, has urged a sliding scale of rebates based on
age, to encourage those who have personal pensions to hold on to them as
they get older. That view has been echoed by the Institute for Fiscal
Studies, an economic think-tank, which argues that the present system costs
more in incentives than it saves.
While personal pensions remain a booming business for the insurance
companies which sell them, they risk being undermined by their own success.
The over-eager sales agent and the drain on the public purse from incentive
payments could threaten the popularity of the product.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
