<DATE>920717
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (17): Small print
that sounded the pension alarm - Malcolm Allbutt worked for a company that
was taken over by Robert Maxwell. After the pension fund had also been
absorbed, he read the annual report, and was horrified by what he learned .
. . / Hindsight
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MALCOLM ALLBUTT had a terrible shock when he read through his company
pension fund annual report last year.
He worked for AGB, a market research company which had been taken over by
Maxwell Communications Corporation the previous year. Its pension fund, of
which he was still a member and into which he had contributed for 22 years,
had now been incorporated with that of the main group.
The report was more informative than some, and listed the top 20 investments
made by the scheme. They were principally in equities.
Pension funds make savings for 'widows and orphans'. Although they often
invest in speculative ventures at the edges of their portfolio, the ballast
is usually in large and secure companies, which have the kind of names
people will recognise - the ICIs, BPs and Marks &amp; Spencers.
Mr Allbutt was therefore horrified to discover that with the exception of a
couple of printing companies - De La Rue and EMAP - and MCC itself, he had
never heard of any of them.
The portfolio seemed to be dominated by the detritus of Maxwell's worldwide
acquisition spree - for example, the seventh biggest holding was in Official
Airlines Guide 'C' Loan Stock. Other less familiar names - such as Agence
Havas and Quebecor - turned out to be large media and printing groups.
Ploughing through the list, it was possible to find out that Teva
Pharmaceutical was an Israeli drug company, while IBI Holding was also a
Maxwell-owned company. Euris and Marceau Investissements were both French
investment vehicles which Robert Maxwell had backed in a bid for French
banking giant Societe Generale.
In short, the portfolio had no logic, beyond its use as a support for
Maxwell's financial forays. While some of the printing groups within it were
strong and reputable companies, it was still unusual for a cautious pension
fund manager to concentrate holdings so narrowly in one sector.
As Mr Allbutt later put it to a Commons select committee, he was 'more than
a little horrified' to see where the money was going. He pointed the list
out to a colleague, closer to retirement, whose reply was: 'Ah yes, but is
there anything there?' At the time, this was still tongue in cheek.
Mr Allbutt decided that the time had come to get out - he could not rely on
this pension fund to pay him a pension.
Unfortunately, the Maxwell pension funds were slow to move - one of Mr
Allbutt's friends who had left the company still found that it took 18
months to receive a transfer value. The employees believe that many of these
delays were deliberate.
Last year, as Maxwell himself went over the side of the Lady Ghislaine, and
his financial empire fast disintegrated in its wake, time was not on the
side of pension fund members.
In early December, Mr Allbutt received the details of what his pension
transfer value would be.
The next day, he was informed that the transfer value was inoperative, as
the fund's assets had been frozen. He had acted as soon as he could, but
still not in time.
Subsequent events confirmed all his worst fears.
In March this year, Clay &amp; Partners, the consulting actuaries appointed to
wind up the four Maxwell pension schemes, announced that about Pounds 40m
was missing from the AGB pension scheme.
The scheme had access to about Pounds 20m in assets - when it should have
had around Pounds 60m.
So, for the time being, Mr Allbutt's contributions to that pension fund are
lost. He has now had to make new arrangements, and has a considerably more
secure personal pension with Scottish Widows.
Could it happen again? Mr Allbutt admits that he, like most of his
colleagues, had never found pensions at all interesting. Had he not been
worried by Maxwell's behaviour, he would not even have checked when he did -
reports of the pension scheme were advertised on company noticeboards as
being available, but were not sent to members individually.
He added: 'You get a lot of creatures like Maxwell who cajole and threaten
people. He had the reputation of being an impetuous and irrational
character. At the time, asking questions could well have put one's job on
the line.'
Hopes of compensation are now slender, as Mr Allbutt, although in his
fifties, is near the back of the queue for compensation. If he is to have
access to his savings, he says, compensation will not be 'terribly useful'
unles the AGB fund is totally refilled. He is determined to maintain
pressure to make sure this happens.
For the time being, he takes the episode very philosophically. 'You hadn't
better ask any of us what we think of Maxwell. He was a crook. But one has
to live one's life.'
And there is also the consolation that Maxwell's theft has provoked some
long overdue action. A government-appointed committee is now considering a
compensation scheme for company pensions, and is likely to force much
greater disclosure of fund management activities. Even changes to trust law
are possible.
But for the time being, how can you best spot potential misuse of your
pension fund? Mr Allbutt's experience provides many of the keys. Actuaries
at Noble Lowndes suggest that you start by finding out about the trustees:
Is there employee or trade union representation?
Is there an independent professional trustee?
Are the trustees all directors of the company?
Then read all the information you are sent, which should soon reveal if
something is amiss. Noble Lowndes suggests you look at the following:
The latest audited accounts and report to members - particularly those from
auditors and actuaries.
Reports on investments. Are the top 10 investment holdings in companies in
big reputable companies, or are they companies like Euris or Teva
Pharmaceutical, of which you have never heard?
Are significant amounts of funds invested in the employing company, or lent
back to it? (This one requires careful scrutiny. AGB's scheme had money in
Maxwell Communications, which was noticeable enough, but there was plenty
more inward investment to be unearthed).
Are investments concentrated in a small number of shares? In the case of
AGB, the top 20 holdings in a fund running to tens of millions of pounds
made up 65.6 per cent - not the kind of figure you will find in the ICI
Pension Fund or the Foreign &amp; Colonial Investment Trust.
If the actuarial valuation says the fund is in deficit, what plans are there
to remedy it? Had this question been raised publicly in the Maxwell case, no
convincing answer could have been forthcoming.
Finally, if the trustees do not give you the information you want, contact
the Occupational Pensions Advisory Service (tel 071 233-8080), which can if
necessary refer your complaint to the Pensions Ombudsman. The name of a
solicitor with pensions knowledge can be obtained from the Association of
Pension Lawyers (tel 071 628-9151).
All of this may help you make an escape in time, if another fraud is being
perpetrated. But all these measures are stop-gaps. Long-term change is
needed.
Mr Allbutt's views are clear: 'The secrecy which has surrounded pension
funds can and must stop. We've got to lift the curtain to have more employee
representation and proper regular communication to fund members.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XV
</PAGE>
