<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (9): Weak figures
leave New York investors little to look forward to - Equities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
REMEMBER THE double-dip? Euphoria in the wake of the Gulf war victory in
1991 briefly spurred economic activity across the US, only for stagnation to
set in soon after.
Now, there is talk of a triple-dip, with a few people on Wall Street warning
that the US economy could be going into reverse for the third time in two
and a half years.
The triple-dippers are a trifle over-pessimistic, but the lacklustre nature
of the recovery has been worrying. Gross domestic product grew by 2.7 per
cent in the first quarter, but in the wake of recent poor economic numbers,
GDP growth in the second quarter will probably be below 2 per cent.
This slowdown in economic activity has put a dampener on stock market
sentiment. During the second quarter, share prices made little ground.
As of the penultimate day of June, the Dow Jones Industrial Average had
advanced just 2.6 per cent to 3,319.86, while the Standard &amp; Poor's 500 had
risen 1.3 per cent to 408.91.
Investors, meanwhile, lost faith in growth stocks, which helps explain why
the Nasdaq composite index, undermined by big falls in once-high flying
biotech and healthcare companies, dropped 7.5 per cent during the three
months to 558.80.
The quarter did not start as gloomily as it ended. April was marked by some
surprisingly good three-monthly corporate earnings - even Ford and General
Motors managed to post a profit - and a modest easing of monetary policy by
the Federal Resere. This, plus some encouraging numbers on retail sales and
the housing market during May, contributed to a slow, if uneven, rise in
share values. Cyclical stocks - those most likely to benefit from a recovery
 -attracted the most demand.
Yet there were hiccups along the way, including the riots in Los Angeles,
which showed that the recovery was not reaching into the nation's cities,
and the bankruptcy of Olympia &amp; York (O&amp;Y), the Canadian property developer
and a big borrower from New York banks.
By the start of June, the Dow had reached 3,400. That, however, proved to be
the limit of the market's achievements. The warning signs of a correction
had already been evident in the poor performance of the S&amp;P 500 and the
Nasdaq composite, which lagged behind the Dow throughout the quarter - proof
that confidence in the market was not broadly spread.
Over the next few weeks, the Dow dropped more than 100 points, as concern
about the economy grew in the wake of bad news on retail sales and
employment. Worst of all, the recovery in the housing market appeared to
have stalled, the result of a rise in mortgage rates during the quarter.
By the end of June, investors had little to look forward to, although weak
economic figures had bolstered hopes that the Fed might lower interest
rates. With election politics sowing uncertainty, economic growth slowing,
and no immediate interest rate cut in sight, the outlook for share prices as
the third quarter opened was none too bright.
Canada mimicked the US. Its economic recovery was sluggish, and O&amp;Y did
little to help sentiment, leaving Canadian investors hoping the US Fed would
ease policy, paving the way for lower Canadian rates. During the quarter the
Toronto Stock Exchange 300
composite index fell by 1 per cent.
Mexico suffered a big reversal, not totally unexpected given the dramatic
nature of the market's rally. The Bolsa index fell by 14.6 per cent in the
April-to-June period. Investors were concerned about the still-unsigned
North American Free Trade Agreement, the weak world economy, and the
possibility that Mexican unions might sell their big stake in
telecommunications giant Telmex.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page X
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-12684</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGQBQADLFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920717
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (8): Analysts
predict some nasty surprises among European results - Equities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONTINUED WEAKNESS in the Japanese equity market and Denmark's 'no' to the
Maastricht Treaty eroded gains made by continental European bourses earlier
in the second quarter.
But the overall performance for Europe was helped by the UK, which had been
given a hefty boost by the Conservative victory in the general election.
According to the FT-Actuaries World Indices, Europe including the UK rose
0.2 per cent on the quarter, but excluding the UK it fell 2.2 per cent.
Some analysts expect European stock markets to have a difficult time in the
third quarter. They expect some nasty surprises to emerge from the first
half results reporting season, in particular from cyclical industries, such
as bulk chemicals. Analysts have already started to downgrade their earnings
forecasts in anticipation of sharply lower second quarter results.
'People are not likely to be new investors at current levels,' says Mr Gary
Dugan, European strategist at Baring Securities. He expects a fall of 5 per
cent or more across continental bourses over the summer.
In its global strategy review for the third quarter, UBS Philips and Drew is
also negative about world equity markets, which it views as very expensive
to underlying earnings. 'Earnings cuts are likely over the summer, and
equities will continue to struggle,' it predicts.
Germany is its market of choice in this environment, because it believes the
German economy can buck the trend of slower economic growth, that German
company balance sheets remain strong, and that German companies will be the
first to take advantage when the industrial cycle finally turns up.
Mr Dugan is neutral on Germany, because the negative impact of slowing
economic growth and dimming hopes of an interest rate cut in the fourth
quarter is offset by prospects of strong import growth in the US, which will
draw in capital goods from Germany. France, on the other hand, is unlikely
to make much progress before its referendum on the Maastricht Treaty, which
may not be held until September.
Goldman Sachs says that, on the premise that uncertainty relating to
European Monetary Union (Emu) is likely to remain a dominant theme over the
short term, it advises investors to opt for markets which are least
vulnerable to monetary union, such as Germany, the Netherlands, and
Switzerland.
Denmark's refusal to endorse closer European union troubled Spanish and
Italian equities, as Emu's planned 'convergence' of European economic
indicators was thrown into doubt. Emu was seen as helping to reduce
inflation in southern European economies. According to the FT-A World
Indices, Spain fell by 7.6 per cent in local currency terms, while Italy
fell by 8.9 per cent.
Mr Stephen Hughes, Spanish analyst at Nikko Europe, believes that the fall
in the Madrid stock market, fuelled by macro-economic fears and financial
problems at some well-known companies, has been exaggerated. He is cautious
of the market in the next quarter, because of the general uncertainty about
the direction of global stock markets over the summer. However, he
recommends picking up stocks on a 12-month view.
Italy was paralysed by the lack of a government until the end of the
quarter; but repeated breakdowns in Milan's new
electronic trading system, blamed on thunder storms, have also deterred
fresh investment, sending the Comit index to a low for the year.
Goldman Sachs says the short-term outlook for the market depends largely on
the prospects for budgetary control and electoral reform. 'If the
politicians begin to put their house in order, this could lead to a
sustained re-rating of Italian equities,' the broker adds.
</TEXT>
