<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (10): Tokyo
languishes but the China factor helps to lift Hong Kong - Equities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THINGS COULD hardly look gloomier for the Tokyo stock market. The Nikkei
Stock Average is down more than 30 per cent since the beginning of the year,
and market participants foresee no short-term recovery.
The past quarter's bad news included worries over the stability of the
financial system, weak corporate earnings results and bankruptcies at
leading companies.
The index fell through 19,000 at the start of April, despite a 75 basis
point cut in the official discount rate by the Bank of Japan on the last day
of March. Traders blamed the central bank's slow response to the weakening
economy, and the fact that that the anticipated move had already been
discounted into share prices.
Share prices weakened further as anxiety about bad loans at the leading
banks and the soundness of the financial system itself spread among
investors. The index plunged through 17,000 and 16,000 on
worse-than-expected corporate earnings forecasts by leading brokerages,
following the results season, and rumours of bankruptcies at leading
property-related companies.
Investors have remained absent from the market as the Nikkei has fallen to
its lowest levels since 1986. Forecasts of its next support level range from
14,000 to 12,000. However, analysts have become reluctant to point to a
bottom, because of investors' lack of confidence.
Meanwhile, elsewhere in the Pacific Rim region, things look brighter.
Traders in Hong Kong raised their glasses in May, as the Hang Seng Index
surged above the critical 6,000 level. The Hong Kong market has seen
substantial buying by US pension funds; and recently the return of the
locals, who had been reluctant to come in due to sour memories of the crash
of 1987, has doubled daily turnover to around HKDollars 3bn.
In addition to the downward pressure on interest rates, political statements
by Chinese leaders, supporting economic reforms using capitalist methods,
have sparked a rally in China-related stocks, encouraging buying by
investors who want an indirect exposure to China's potential economic
growth.
However, the Hong Kong market remains vulnerable to political events.
Uncertainty about the renewal of China's 'most favoured nation' trading
status with the US, and the debate about the financing of the new airport,
could cause volatility as the Hang Seng index continues to test new highs.
Australian equities - after a rally in late April helped by lower
inflationary pressure and lower bond yields - remained in the 1,625 to 1,675
range for the most of May and June. Evidence of an economic recovery has
been slow to emerge, and the All Ordinaries index may remain within that
range until clear signs of a rebound appear.
Bangkok, which was hit by civil unrest, seems to offer the most potential on
the upside. Towards the end of the quarter, the SET index was more than 9
per cent off its peak at 750. 'The market is oversold,' says Mr David
Shairp, research director at Barclays de Zoete Wedd, in Hong Kong.
After a firm first quarter, the SET index climbed to the year's peak of 832
at the beginning of April. However, it weakened on political uncertainty
surrounding General Suchinda Kraprayoon's government.
The market has since recovered from the 660 level, its lowest since December
1991, posted after the military crushed protests against the appointment of
General Suchinda. Efforts by financial authorities and the new government to
restore confidence in Thailand's political system and financial markets have
been welcomed by investors. Additionally, prospects of an economic slowdown
and a narrowing current account deficit point to scope for lower interest
rates, a positive sign for share prices.
</TEXT>
