<DOCNO>FT923-12687</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGQBQADIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920717
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (6): Cash may be
better for the nerves - The FT-A World index finished the quarter 10 points
down in sterling terms, as global equity markets produced a negative 7.5 per
cent return / Equities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DOMINICK COYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SECOND quarter was another miserable one for equity investors, and the
choice of markets didn't matter much - provided you avoided Japan, yet
again.
The Nikkei index, which had dropped through the psychologically important
20,000 support level in the first quarter, ended the second below 16,000.
Over the quarter, Japan had a negative total return, measured in sterling,
of minus-16.2 per cent.
Most other equity markets did a lot better, although still in negative
territory. In sterling terms, the FT-Actuaries World index closed the period
at 107.87, or some 10 index points off its level on March 31. In terms of
total returns, global equity markets produced a negative 7.5 per cent for
sterling investors.
All in all, it's been a bad first half, although there were a few moderately
bright markets over the past quarter, notably Hong Kong, the UK and
Switzerland. In the last Quarterly Review, this column foresaw uncertain
times immediately ahead, and advised private investors and cautious fund
managers to stay overweight in cash. Anyone who did so was ahead of the game
at the end of June.
Why the dismal performances? In a word: uncertainty. The unexpected return
of a majority Conservative government in Britain did produce the almost
inevitable bounce in UK equities, but much of it did not hold against
continuing concern about the economy. Nonetheless, there was a positive
total return of 4.7 per cent.
On the wider European front, Danish voters' rejection of the Maastricht
treaty put a big question-mark over moves towards European monetary union, a
mood only partially relieved by an enthusiastic Irish vote in favour. France
holds its Maastricht referendum in September, amid fears that the specific
issue could be clouded by the domestic unpopularity of President Francois
Mitterrand. This is likely to keep the European equity sector uncertain over
the next quarter.
Investor confidence was not helped when a major share flotation by Ireland's
GPA Group, the world's biggest aircraft leasing company, was pulled at the
last minute for lack of institutional interest, particularly in the US. This
has cast a shadow over an even bigger share sale, scheduled for July 27, by
the Wellcome Trust, of a large slice of its holdings in the British drugs
company that bears its name. Wellcome is no GPA, but jumpy equity markets
would like to see the sale safely away.
The Wall Street picture seems no more secure. Election jitters are in the
air, with the maverick Ross Perot unnerving President George Bush from the
right and the Democrat, Bill Clinton, snapping from the left. The proclaimed
US economic recovery appears anaemic, or at best only modest, and Wall
Street over the last quarter moved sideways. Dollar investors saw a mere 1.6
per cent in total return.
Tokyo, measured by the Nikkei, actually chose the last trading day of the
quarter to record a three-month low at 15,785, with the few remaining
optimists there hoping for some kind of market support from the
supplementary budget promised for later in the summer.
Where do the markets go from here, amid all this political and economic
uncertainty? The big global players report that they are cutting back on
equity holdings, switching to bonds and cash. But some German houses claim
to be buying selectively in London and in a number of other European markets
 -the rationale being that lower German interest rates (when they eventually
materialise) could start off an equity buying spree in many continental
markets.
But with so much gloom and uncertainty about, it is mainly the contrarians
who see good buying opportunities at the moment. For the rest, and
especially over the next quarter, staying overweight in cash may be best for
the nerves.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
