<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (5): A triple-B
portfolio reshuffle - . . . in which Mr Ledger and Mr Stagge help John and
Alison beat an attack of mid-life ennui, and the birthday season looks
brighter / The Plowshares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BEVERLY CHANDLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JOHN PLOWSHARE is facing his 50th birthday. A sobering thought for anyone,
but particularly sobering when you haven't been keeping up the payments into
your personal pensions because of the effect of the recession on your firm.
The thought of getting older - can it really be half a century? - and of
getting older on less cash than he had planned, has kept John distracted and
miserable for several days.
It has finally got on Alison's nerves, particularly as she, too, has been
distracted and miserable and nobody has noticed. Her misery stems from a
feeling of guilt, that nobody has made sufficient fuss of Lucy and Toby, who
have achieved 21 and 18 respectively in the past year.
These were birthdays which, in pre-recession days, would have been marked by
the Plowshares with a fairly substantial party at the very least.
John and Alison finally meet, both distracted and miserable, wandering
around the conservatory late one evening. 'What is the matter with you?'
each asks the other. And sad stories are exchanged.
'I feel so old,' howls John, collapsing on to an ancient and uncomfortable
Rattan chair. 'I've got friends retiring at 50, but there's no way I can
even think of retiring for at least another 20 years on my current pension
provision.'
And I feel such a killjoy,' moans Alison. 'We could have done a little more
for the children with their coming-of-age birthdays, let alone for your 50th
birthday. I'm so bored with being careful with cash on a day-to-day basis.'
The only obvious source of cash is the Plowshares' savings and portfolio of
unit trusts, which they put together 18 months ago under the sensible advice
of Mr Stagge, of stockbrokers Stagge &amp; Hoppitt, and Mr Ledger, their
accountant.
Since then, they have received endless bits of paper and statements and the
odd thing to sign, but they have no clear idea of what their holdings are
actually worth.
John and Alison make an appointment, and later in the week go off to visit
Mr Stagge. At the time of sorting out their portfolios, he had recommended
that they move the bulk of their money out of the building society, where
interest rates on deposit accounts were dropping, and invest it in unit
trusts.
This appears to have been rather a good idea. To the Plowshares' surprise
and joy, their portfolios are looking extremely healthy.
increased by 29.6 per cent on an offer-to-offer basis over the 18 months.
The Plowshares' original Pounds 50,000 is now worth Pounds 64,817, and, much
to Alison's pleasure in particular, the best performing part of the
portfolio has turned out to be the Pacific Basin funds that she was
particularly keen on.
The Peps have managed a respectable performance, too. The Plowshares put a
further Pounds 6,000 each in from the building society in this tax year and
now have Pounds 24,000 invested in Peps - now worth Pounds 28,000. Beyond
that, they have Pounds 26,000 rainy-day money in the building society, which
is kept in Alison's name for tax purposes.
However, it is not all good news. Flushed with the thrill of having
increased their capital fairly easily, the Plowshares move on to visit Mr
Ledger, the accountant.
'You're not nearly up to scratch on your pensions, Mr Plowshare,' says Mr
Ledger, sternly. 'I would recommend that, as your portfolio has done so well
under Mr Stagge's care, you take your Pounds 5,800 capital gains tax
allowance out of your unit trust portfolio, before indexation, and catch up
on your premium holiday. Say, Pounds 2,000 for the last two years plus an
additional Pounds 1,800 into your pensions.'
It turns out that, at age 50, John is entitled to put 25 per cent of his net
relevant earnings from his partnership into a pension and gain 40 per cent
tax relief; so he is well within his allowances.
In fact, if he had sufficient cash, he could apply a back-tracking technique
over the last six tax years to take advantage of unused tax relief. However,
his cash-flow clearly won't allow this at the moment.
Meanwhile, Alison could also take up to Pounds 5,800 tax-free out of her
portfolio if she wished, and Mr Ledger recommends that she also put Pounds
750 into a new personal pension plan, which she can pay net of basic-rate
tax relief. Alison decides that she would like to gift Pounds 1,000 to her
daughter Lucy and Pounds 500 to Toby from her capital gain. This, it turns
out, is well within the annual Pounds 3,000 exemption for gifts, and so will
not incur any tax.
A further recommendation is not so popular with Alison. 'You could always
transfer some of your portfolio gain, or some of the building society money
over to your husband, so that he could make a further contribution into his
pension,' says Mr Ledger.
After some noisy debate, over which we will draw a veil, Alison agrees to
transfer Pounds 3,000 of the capital gain on her portfolio to John, with
which he can top up his pension - a transfer which attracts no taxation.
On their way home, Alison reflects, rather mournfully: 'I suppose I feel
like a generous sort of person now - which is some comfort. I mean, I've
given away Pounds 4,500 to my immediate family. . . But I still feel like a
killjoy.'
'And I still feel old,' adds John.
But the Plowshares are sensible people; and it doesn't take them long to
work out that the solution to this one is a party to mark all three
birthdays - and to help Alison continue to feel generous.
Help in compiling this feature was provided by SM Searle, from Gerrard
Vivian Gray, who put together the portfolio, and David Oldridge, of Hill
Oldridge, who supplied financial advice.
Who's who
The Plowshares, a couple in their late forties, live in one of the smarter
bits of North London. John is a partner in an architectural practice and
earned Pounds 60,000 last year, though this year times have proved harder
and his earnings are down to Pounds 50,000. . . Alison has a part-time job
as a receptionist for the local GP. The Plowshares have two children: Lucy,
who is 21, at university in the Midlands, and Toby, 18, about to leave
school. . . Following the deaths of John's parents and his subsequent
inheritance, the Plowshares have a portfolio of unit trusts, a Pep each and
some rainy-day money in the building society.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-12689</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGQBQADGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920717
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (4): Something for
everyone - Increased government borrowing is a fillip for products that
advisers don't always mention / Fixed interest 3: National Savings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL SAVINGS products are an obvious investment for those seeking a
fixed return on their money. Since they are issued by the government, they
are completely safe and they offer attractive rates of return.
They tend to be ignored by financial advisers, because they do not pay
commission, but application forms are easy to get hold of over the post
office counter.
Fixed rates are available on Certificates - the index-linked and 37th issue
 -the Yearly Plan, Children's bonus bonds, Capital bonds, and the new First
Option bond, launched on July 7.
The First (Fixed Interest Rate Savings Tax-Paid) Option Bond carries a
guaranteed interest rate of 7.75 per cent net (equivalent to 10.34 per cent
gross) on a minimum of Pounds 1,000. Tax is deducted at source, and the bond
is aimed at the country's 25.1m basic-rate taxpayers. A higher rate of 8.05
per cent net is payable on Pounds 20,000 and above.
The rate is guaranteed for a year, but National Savings can announce a new
rate of interest for new issues at any time.
The bond is part of the government's strategy to raise Pounds 28bn for the
public sector borrowing requirement.
The suitability of the fixed rate products you choose depends on your tax
status:
Higher-rate taxpayer: National Savings certificates are the best choice,
because they are free of income tax and capital gains tax. The 37th issue
certificate offers a guaranteed return of 8 per cent per annum compound if
held for five years. The minimum investment is Pounds 25 and the maximum
Pounds 7,500, although an additional Pounds 10,000 can be invested from
matured certificates of earlier issues. The return is the equivalent of
13.33 per cent to a 40 per cent payer and 10.67 per cent to a basic-rate
taxpayer.
The index-linked certificates pay 4.5 per cent per annum above the rate of
inflation, measured by the Retail Prices Index. You can hold a maximum of
Pounds 10,000, and returns are again tax-free. It is possible to hold both
sets of certificates but those wishing to choose between the two have to
make a decision on where they expect the inflation rate to be within the
next five years. If you think it will be above 4 per cent per annum, then
index-linked certificates are going to be the more attractive.
The Yearly Plan is a scheme for saving once a month for a year, in order to
buy a Savings Certificate at the end of that year. Savers pay a fixed amount
(between Pounds 20 and Pounds 400) by monthly standing order. This means
that the maximum value Savings Certificate that you can obtain through the
Yearly Plan is Pounds 2,400.
The certificate must be held for a further four years to earn the average
current return of 8 per cent tax-free per annum. Since payments in the first
year are staggered, the total return will be lower than if the investor had
placed Pounds 2,400 in the 37th issue certificates at the outset. Savers can
hold the Yearly Plan in addition to the certificates.
Non-taxpayers: Capital Bonds also offer a guaranteed return if held for five
years, but are subject to tax. Non-taxpayers will have the benefit of
receiving interest gross, because the tax is not deducted on the interest
payment. The present Series D offers a gross return of 10.75 per cent per
annum, compound over five years. The bonds are sold in multiples of Pounds
100, to a maximum of Pounds 100,000.
Basic rate taxpayers: This gap in the product range has been met by the new
one-year First Option bond. The bond pays a fixed rate of interest (see
above) net of basic rate tax on a minimum of Pounds 1,000, guaranteed for
one year at a time, although investors can hold the bond for more than a
year if they like the sound of the next annual fixed rate. Interest will be
added annually.
However, there are stiff penalties for early withdrawal. If the bond is
cashed in before the first anniversary, no interest will be paid.
Withdrawals between anniversaries will attract half interest for the period
since the previous anniversary. If you do not cash in the bond, any revised
rate will be paid automatically for a further year.
The maximum holding is Pounds 250,000. Non-taxpayers can reclaim the tax
that has been deducted ast source.
Basic rate taxpayers who want a fixed rate over a five-year period will be
marginally better off buying Capital Bonds than the 37th issue certificates,
because even after deducting 25 per cent tax, the return will be 8.063 per
cent per annum.
Children: The issue B Children's Bonus Bond pays a tax-free and guaranteed
return equal to 10.9 per cent per annum over its first five years.
These can be bought in multiples of Pounds 25 to a maximium holding of
Pounds 1,000. Adults will have to purchase the bond for children under the
age of 16, and there are no more returns after the 21st birthday.
Disadvantages: The main disadvantage with National Savings certificates and
bonds is that they do not pay an income: all of the return comes from the
increase in value on maturity. They are also inflexible - the returns cited
are only achieved if you hold them for exactly five years. If you sell them
beforehand, the returns are reduced; if you forget to redeem them on
maturity, the certificates start to earn the unattractive general extension
rate of 5.01 per cent.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
