<DATE>920717
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (1): Disappointment
follows the brief honeymoon - But UK savers can still earn 9 per cent on
fixed income investments, with inflation only 4 per cent / Keynote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT WAS a nice honeymoon, while it lasted. But somehow the same old economic
problems have remained to perplex the new John Major government on its
return to power. So the second quarter in the financial markets ended on a
disappointing note, especially given that it had begun so ecstatically after
the unexpected outright Conservative victory on April 9.
Certainly, the month after the election was highly bullish. The London stock
market leapt back to life, fuelled by hopes that the return of the Tories
would boost business and consumer confidence and jolt the British economy
back to life. From a low of 2382.7 on April 3 the FT-SE 100 Index advanced
to an all-time peak of 2737.8 on May 11, a gain of nearly 15 per cent.
The rise in share prices was boosted on May 5 by a post-election cut of  1/2
per cent to 10 per cent in sterling short-term interest rates, reflecting
the British currency's much stronger position within the European exchange
rate mechanism.
Meanwhile, the authorities got on energetically with the task of selling the
huge volume of gilt-edged securities needed to finance the projected
government deficit. A public sector borrowing requirement of Pounds 28bn is
officially forecast for 1992-93, and even more next year. As the recession
bites deeper, moreover, many outside forecasters are increasing their
estimates of just how big these deficits will turn out to be in the next few
years.
In post-election conditions, however, the Bank of England, as the Treasury's
agent in the gilt-edged market, was able to get busy with bond sales,
starting with a Pounds 1.6bn surge on election night itself. There have
subsequently been several individual auctions of up to Pounds 2.75bn of
gilts, and it is estimated that the Bank sold about Pounds 12.5bn gross of
bonds in the April-June quarter.
The government has also given the orders for National Savings to go out on
an aggressive sales drive in the retail market place. Thus National Savings
has been pulling in about Pounds 400m a month recently, enough to embarrass
the building societies which, in a very tough housing market, are finding it
difficult to compete for funds.
But as the stock market boom continued into May, cracks began to appear in
the enthusiasm of investors. It became clear that company results were
coming in below expectations. Economic statistics were disappointing, and
the fall in the first quarter's national income turned out to have been
worse than expected at 0.5 per cent for the quarter and 1.5 per cent over
twelve months. The 'green shoots' of recovery had failed to appear. By the
end of May, the full disaster of the Canary Wharf project became apparent as
the development followed its Canadian parent Olympia &amp; York into bankruptcy.
Overseas, the Tokyo market began to resume its devastating fall, reaching a
level some 60 per cent below its all-time high at the beginning of 1990. Not
that Tokyo's agony has had much impact on markets elsewhere, and indeed Wall
Street managed to struggle to a new all-time peak at the beginning of June.
But that was only on the basis of the 30 constituents of the Dow Jones
Average, and the more broadly-based equity market US indices have remained
below their January highs.
Closer to home, German overheating remained a big problem and hopes of
further interest rate cuts within the ERM have faded badly. Then, at the
beginning of June, came a bolt from the blue: the Danes narrowly rejected
the Maastricht treaty in a referendum.
Expectations of a steady advance by European Community member states towards
monetary union were suddenly dashed. Sterling was one of the currencies to
suffer as the Deutsche Mark once again strengthened. Finally, at the end of
June, the former prime minister Lady Thatcher delivered another blow to
confidence in the pound, by attacking Maastricht and saying there could be
no economic recovery for the UK while interest rates were held so high by
the requirements of the ERM.
All in all, June was a bad month for the markets. While the currency and
gilts came under pressure, the stock market too was troubled. Over-optimism
about prospects became exposed as leading companies like ICI and Pilkington
warned that no recovery was in sight. Big new issues planned in a more
buoyant period, or postponed until after the election, arrived just as
sentiment crumbled; the Pounds 430m GPA flotation had to be embarrassingly
abandoned at the very last moment on June 18. A boardroom upheaval on June
25 at troubled BP saw the share price tumble amidst fears of a slashed
dividend. Suddenly the market began to fear a whole wave of dividend cuts as
prudent distribution came back into fashion.
By the end of the month, the Footsie index had lost about 8 per cent
compared with the May high. However, there remained a small gain on the
quarter as a whole. The rate of return - capital gain plus dividend income -
on equities for a standard rate taxpayer for the three months was about 4
per cent.
You would have done better in fixed-income securities, however. The return
on 15-year gilts was about 9 per cent during the quarter. This continues a
pattern which has been seen during the 1990s so far, that equities have
proved to be disappointing and bonds have provided a better return. But even
bonds have failed to match the outstanding investment returns which were
seen during the 1980s.
Little is likely to change. The British economy faces a long process of
adjustment to lower inflation and lower levels of private debt. The world
economy offers little hope of external assistance, with Japan running into
trouble and the United States facing its own problems of too much debt and
too little growth.
The huge selling pressure from the Bank of England in the gilt-edged market
will continue to dominate the investment scene. British companies are going
to find it very hard to earn returns on capital which could enable them to
pay the progressive dividends needed if the stock market is to perform
strongly compared with gilts. Sterling may be marginally weak against the
DM, but it is very strong against the dollar, so British companies are
losing competitiveness in dollar markets.
For the time being, the newly-elected government is under no significant
pressure to do anything about the continuing recession. The second quarter
GDP figures may show a marginal pick-up when they are eventually calculated
in September, but independent economists now calculate that the British
economy will show just about zero growth in 1992 as a whole.
The near-term question is whether the government will announce major public
spending cutbacks in order to prevent the public sector borrowing
requirement from ballooning still further. Eventually there may be a more
serious debate about whether the government should cut and run from the ERM,
Thatcher-style. If this happens, it will have very important investment
implications. But at present it is still scarcely above the horizon.
For the moment, the stock market should be treated with caution, and
investors should think themselves lucky that they can still earn 9 per cent
on fixed income investments when inflation is only 4 per cent, and on a
slowly falling trend.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
