<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / International Capital Markets: NationsBank turns in 22%
income rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE recovery trend in US banking continued yesterday when a 22 per cent rise
in net income was reported by NationsBank, the large south-eastern regional
group formed last year by the merger of C&amp;S Sovran and NCNB.
Yesterday's bank results also included a 65 per cent jump in net profits at
the Chicago-based Continental Bank and a profitable quarter for the
Connecticut-based Shawmut National, compared with a loss in the second
quarter of 1991.
NationsBank's net profit was Dollars 251m in the second quarter, up from
Dollars 206m in the same period last year. Earnings per share were Dollars
1, some 14 per cent higher than the 88 cents of a year ago.
The bank, the fourth biggest in the US with Dollars 111bn of assets and more
than 1,800 offices in 10 states, said net loan write-offs were Dollars 141m
in the quarter, down significantly from Dollars 262m a year ago.
Second quarter bad debt provisions were almost halved year-on-year, from
Dollars 294m to Dollars 150m. Non-performing loans declined by Dollars 126m
during the quarter, to Dollars 1.76bn.
At Continental Bank, second quarter net earnings totalled Dollars 51m, up
from Dollars 31m a year ago. On a per share basis earnings were 78 cent
against 41 cents.
Although net interest revenue was unchanged at Dollars 119m, Mr Thomas
Theobald, chairman, said reduced operating expenses and lower bad debt
provisions contributed to the profits rise.
Continental Bank's provisions were Dollars 25m against Dollars 63m in the
second quarter of 1991. Operating expenses dropped by 16 per cent to Dollars
134m in the quarter.
Shawmut, an indicator of the state of the New England economy, recorded an
Dollars 8.6m net profit in the quarter, compared with a Dollars 58.7m loss a
year ago. Earnings per share were nine cents against a loss of 81 cents.
</TEXT>
