Christopher Woodgate, who has quit as chief executive of London's IMI
Securities, is one stockbroker who believes that institutional fashions are
going full circle. He is betting on the swing back towards old-style
partnerships by setting up ICE Securities.
A few years ago, London's established broking partnerships were swallowed up
by large, mostly well-capitalised banks. Now, Woodgate thinks that boutiques
like ICE, which opens for business in September, may once again be the way
to woo clients in niche markets.
Woodgate, a veteran of several new broking ventures, set up IMI Securities,
which specialises in Italian and Austrian stocks, in partnership with
