<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUL 92 / Performance pay's value is questioned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE value of performance-related pay to employers and employees has been
called into question by a poll of 1,600 British Telecom managers.
The poll, conducted by the Society of Telecom Executives, the union
representing 25,000 managers and professionals in the industry, found that
only 7 per cent of the sample thought PRP schemes improved their
performance.
Some 66 per cent of the sample thought that performance pay was applied
unfairly, and more than 70 per cent thought that bonuses were arbitrary and
that they undermined teamwork.
The Society of Telecom Executives said the survey found that women fared
less well under performance pay systems than men, even when they were
meeting the same targets of performance standards.
The survey also found that more than 70 per cent of BT's managers suffer
from work-related stress, while some 57 per cent suffer from low morale.
</TEXT>
