<DOCNO>FT923-12807</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGPA3AGEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920716
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / London Stock Exchange: Footsie unable to hold above 2,500
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN ATTEMPT by the UK equity market to extend the recovery of the previous
session faded away yesterday as investors grew increasingly nervous ahead of
this morning's meeting of the Bundesbank's policy-making council. Firmness
in the D-Mark emphasised fears that the German central bank might tighten
policy today, and cast deeper clouds over prospects for UK interest rates.
Blue chip share prices opened strongly, as an initial gain in the September
futures contract on the FT-SE Index buttressed hopes for an extension of the
recovery seen at the close of the previous session. The Footsie quickly
advanced by 17.1, managing once again to move above the 2,500 mark, which
has proved an elusive target recently.
It was soon clear, however, that institutional buying support was sadly
lacking and, as the premium on the Footsie contract faded away, so did the
gain on the underlying index. Although the market held in positive territory
for the rest of the day, there was little genuine support. A sluggish start
on Wall Street, which was 5.68 Dow points off in UK hours, left London to
close in lifeless trading.
The FT-SE Index ended just a net 2.4 up at 2,486.4. Seaq volume remained
low, with the 404m-share total swollen by the completion of Tuesday
afterover of 374.1m on Tuesday represented customer, or retail, business of
only Pounds 854.3m, still a dismal figure from the point of view of the
London-based securities industry.
The lack of investment interest was reflected in the expectedly poor start
for Anglian Group, which opened at a discount to the share offer price after
a poor response to the public offer. Tomorrow brings the start of dealings
in MFI Furniture, which had a similarly unsuccessful journey through the
public sale process. Shares in Wellcome edged higher as the London market
awaited the close of the share offer period at the end of next week.
Traders said the market had been virtually put 'on hold' until the outcome
of today's meeting at the Bundesbank is known. Reiterated political support
for Britain's place in the European exchange rate mechanism left the City of
London to wait nervously for any decision on German monetary disciplines.
Two small trading programmes were identified yesterday, but such was the
lack of enthusiasm in the market that the overall trend of share prices was
not affected.
The banking sector continued to find some support, with the exception of
TSB, which gave ground as hopes for a bid receded. A few very small,
scattered gains among the store shares reflected little more than a
technical rally in a badly battered area of the stock market.
In its latest analysis of the UK economy, Goldman Sachs commented that
'there is now mounting evidence that the Conservatives' election victory has
not proved to be the catalyst required to shake consumers out of their
torpor. This is bad news for the manufacturing recovery which started in
February.'
