<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / International Company News: US banks signal recovery in
sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SECOND-quarter results from four medium-sized US banks yesterday offered
more evidence of an earnings recovery in the sector.
Fleet Financial Group, the Providence, Rhode Island-based bank that last
year acquired the failed Bank of New England (BNE), produced a sharp rise in
net profits, from Dollars 28m to Dollars 71m.
Fleet's earnings rise - 45 cents against 23 cents in terms of earning per
share - was helped by gains on security sales, a lower level of
non-performing assets, and substantial contributions from the Massachusetts
branch operations of the former BNE.
Mr Terrence Murray, chairman, said the results were encouraging, but he
noted that bad debt provisions were increased by Dollars 40m during the
quarter. This was due to lingering uncertainty about the strength of the
economy in the north-east of the US.
He said Fleet's conversion and absorption of the former BNE branch franchise
would be completed by year-end.
The group's total workforce has meanwhile been reduced. At the time of the
acquisition last year, Fleet employed 18,000 people and BNE 11,000; the
combined workforce is now 2,000 less. Fleet's total assets at the end of
June were Dollars 45bn, compared with Dollars 32bn a year ago.
Bank of New York, meanwhile, announced a 45 per cent jump in second-quarter
net income, to Dollars 87m, or Dollars 1.05 per share. The profit rise was
helped by stronger fee income, wider spreads and lower bad debt provisions.
While second-quarter bad debt provisions were Dollars 106m against Dollars
127m a year ago, the level of total non-performing assets fell by 14 per
cent to Dollars 1.1bn. Non-performing commercial property assets declined by
12 per cent.
Two months ago, Bank of New York agreed to acquire the 65-branch New York
retail banking operations of Barclays Bank of the UK, a move that will boost
assets by Dollars 3.2bn. The Bank of New York's total assets at the end of
last month were Dollars 41.3bn.
Another profits rise was announced by Republic New York Corporation, the
holding company of Mr Edmond Safra's Republic National Bank and Manhattan
Savings Bank.
Republic said its net income rose 13.3 per cent to Dollars 63.9m. Earnings
per share were 9.1 per cent higher at Dollars 1.08.
The Minneapolis-based Norwest Corporation, a prominent mid-western bank with
1,725 offices and Dollars 40.6bn of assets, said its net profits were 21 per
cent higher at Dollars 127.9m.
</TEXT>
