<DATE>920716
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / International Company News: SEC adopts new powers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Securities and Exchange Commission, the US financial markets watchdog,
yesterday took on new powers that would make it easier for the agency to
discover whether US securities firms are in financial trouble, writes
Patrick Harverson.
The new rule gives the SEC the right to demand from holding companies
information about their securities subsidiaries, even if the parent is not
regulated by the agency.
The SEC hopes the rule will allow it to discover if a parent company is
having financial problems that could affect a securities firm.
The agency was granted authority to institute the new rule in a reform bill
prompted by the collapse of Drexel Burnham Lambert.
Under the rule, parent companies of securities firms must file quarterly
financial statements giving information on its, and subsidiaries', exposure
to a variety of assets, including securities and commodities, real estate
holdings, and off-balance sheet derivatives such as interest-rate swaps.
</TEXT>
