</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GANNETT, the US publisher of 81 daily newspapers, including USA Today,
yesterday said a recovery in advertising revenues helped it to a 4 per cent
rise in net profits for the second quarter of 1992.
The Virginia-based company said its second-quarter net profit was Dollars
98.745m, while earnings per share were 13 per cent higher at 69 cents.
Wall Street reacted favourably to the profit increase, marking the Gannett
share price Dollars 1 3/8 higher to Dollars 45 3/8 .
Gannett said its second-quarter operating revenues were 2 per cent higher at
Dollars 892.1m. Operating income for the quarter was, meanwhile, 9 per cent
improved at Dollars 176.7m.
The company said its newspaper publishing earnings rose due to higher
advertising and circulation revenues, along with significantly lower
newsprint costs.
At USA Today, the down-market national daily, paid advertising pages
increased by 3 per cent during the quarter.
Broadcasting revenues were unchanged at Dollars 97.5m as revenues from
Gannett's 10 television stations grew by 2 per cent and those from its 15
radio stations declined.
Revenues from Gannett's outdoor advertising division, the largest such
company in North America, fell 4 per cent to Dollars 66.8m in the quarter.
For the first six months of 1992, earnings per share were 16 per cent higher
at Dollars 1.07. Net income was Dollars 154.2m, compared with Dollars 145.1m
in the first half of 1991. Operating revenues for the first six months were
1 per cent better at Dollars 1.7bn.
