<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / International Company News: Prices force Gengold to shelve
mine proposals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WEAK gold price have claimed further casualties. Gengold, the gold arm of
the Gencor group, has been forced to mothball the developing Weltevreden
mine and shelve plans to deepen the No 6 shaft at Winkelhaak.
Mr Gary Maude, managing director, said work had been stopped at Weltevreden
because the gold price was 41 per cent lower than envisaged when the project
was undertaken. He said a price of R45,000 (Dollars 16,304) per kilogram
would be needed to restart the project. The current price is under R31,000
per kilogram.
Mr Maude said the Winkelhaak shaft would be viable if there could be
confidence of a gold price of R32,000 a kilogram. The price, however, was
weakening.
The average price received by group mines in the June quarter was R32,071
per kilogram. Previously announced plans to merge Winkelhaak and Kinross
Gold Mines would be delayed.
A feature of the group's results for the quarter was the substantial
contribution to profits from hedging, a practice Gengold has now adapted
with some enthusiasm. Mr Maude said the group had made hedging profits of
R16.8m during the quarter from the forward selling of nearly 147,000 ounces
of production.
He said hedging profits had accounted for about one-third of the 5 per cent
improvement in group after-tax profits, to R70.6m compared with the previous
quarter. Gengold mines hedge up to 20 per cent of production.
The R1.3bn first-phase capital programme for Oryx mine in the Orange Free
State is continuing.
</TEXT>
