FT  16 JUL 92 / International Company News: US pulp and paper group breaks
even
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON, KAREN ZAGOR and BARBARA DURR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GEORGIA-PACIFIC, the US forest products group, has reported break-even
results for the second quarter, with a sharp drop in pulp and paper profits
partly offset by a big rise in lumber income.
The company announced earlier this month that its results would be 'slightly
better than break-even'.
The break-even figure, compared with net income of Dollars 29m, or 34 cents
a share, in the second quarter of last year when the company was helped by a
Dollars 29m after-tax gain on the sale of forests. Sales for the latest
quarter, at Dollars 3bn, were unchanged from last year.
For the six months, the company reported net income of Dollars 5m, or 6
cents a share, on sales of Dollars 5.88bn, against a net loss of Dollars
44m, or 51 cents, last year, on sales of Dollars 5.76bn.
*****
Dun &amp; Bradstreet, US business information group, yesterday posted
second-quarter net income of Dollars 128.8m, or 72 cents a share, compared
with Dollars 119.1m, or 67 cents, a year ago, writes Karen Zagor.
The company has restated its 1991 results to reflect new accounting
standards and the recognition of revenue for software services.
Revenues eased to Dollars 1.16bn from Dollars 1.17bn, reflecting the
divestiture of the communications unit of the company's IMS International
division. Revenue growth for Dun &amp; Bradstreet's portfolio of businesses rose
about 3 per cent in the quarter.
For the first six months, the company had net income of Dollars 227m, or
Dollars 1.27, against Dollars 217.5m, or Dollars 1.22 a year earlier.
Operating revenue slipped to Dollars 2.27bn from Dollars 2.29bn.
*****
American Home Products, the US pharmaceutical group, yesterday turned in
second-quarter net income of Dollars 296.1m, or 94 cents a share, up 12 per
cent from the previous year's earnings of Dollars 265.2m, or 84 cents,
writes Karen Zagor. Sales in the three months to June 30 rose 8 per cent to
Dollars 1.76bn from 1.62bn.
Shares in American Home Products closed Dollars 2 1/8 lower at Dollars 72
3/4 in active trading.
For the first half of 1992, the company's net income rose 14 per cent to
Dollars 702.4m, or Dollars 2.23, from Dollars 617.7m, or Dollars 1.96. Sales
grew 11 per cent to Dollars 3.75bn from 3.38bn.
*****
Reynolds Metals, the second-largest US aluminium group was depressed by weak
aluminium prices in spite of record shipments, writes Barbara Durr in
Chicago.
The company reported second-quarter net income of Dollars 33.1m, or 56 cents
per share, a 46 per cent drop from last year's Dollars 61.4m, or Dollars
1.04. Revenues in the quarter ended June 30 were Dollars 1.49bn, compared
with Dollars 1.52bn a year ago.
In the first half, net income was Dollars 46.4m, or 78 cents per share, on
revenues of Dollars 2.82bn, compared with Dollars 88.9m, or Dollars 1.50, on
revenues of Dollars 2.89.
Shipments for the quarter were a record 393,400 metric tons, up 3.6 per
cent.
