<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / Belling pension fund probe widens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INVESTIGATION into the loss of Pounds 2.1m from the pension fund of
Belling, the cooker manufacturer which went into receivership last May, has
widened to include two companies linked to Mr Clive J Smith, the Midlands
entrepreneur who faces legal actions over his natural resource investments.
The first company is Finchley Investments, the Isle of Man company
administered from Jersey, which Mr Smith has often used to handle some of
his investments. The second is Western &amp; Pacific, a Canadian mining group.
It was 57.4 per cent owned by Mr Smith and his family through Finchley and
another company, Newsham Investments, in May 1991.
Last summer, Belling tried to arrange a Dollars 50m (Pounds 26m) capital
injection through Global Prospect Funding. In advance of the deal, Belling
paid Global Pounds 2.1m as the first year's interest. The company borrowed
the money from its pension fund.
In April this year, when the Dollars 50m was not forthcoming, Belling
demanded security. Global introduced Finchley Investments which put up
shares in Western &amp; Pacific. Belling believed the shares were worth CDollars
1.75m (Pounds 760,000). However, today they are estimated to be worth Pounds
200,000.
The Law Debenture Society, the new independent trustee of the pension fund,
is investigating the fund shortfall and trying to recoup the money. Global
is administered by Mr C J Deacon, a solicitor based in Newcastle-under-Lyme.
He is believed to be helping the society in trying to recover the money.
One of the shareholders in Finchley was Mr Kelvin Myles, who ran the offices
of Bryant &amp; Co, the Jersey accountant which was raided this spring by Jersey
fraud office. Documents found at Bryant &amp; Co have triggered a Serious Fraud
Office investigation into share dealings in Richmond Oil &amp; Gas and Butte
Mining, two companies which Mr Smith had helped float. Bryant &amp; Co also
managed some of Mr Smith's off-shore interests.
Mr Smith, who also has offices in Newcastle-under-Lyme, was unavailable for
comment. He faces litigation from Butte Mining and Sun Glow of the US. Butte
alleges fraud and misrepresentation by more than 70 defendants. Sun Glow is
seeking Dollars 450,000 from Mr Smith allegedly arising from a personal
guarantee. Mr Smith said recently he would contest both actions.
</TEXT>
