<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / Parcelforce sell-off imminent: Heseltine pledges continuing
universal parcel service at affordable tariff
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH, DIANE SUMMERS and DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PARCELFORCE, the loss-making parcel delivery arm of the Post Office, is to
be privatised as soon as possible, Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and
industry secretary, said yesterday
He emphasised there would continue to be a universal parcel service at a
uniform and affordable tariff. 'That is not negotiable,' he told MPs,
indicating that the tariff would remain a matter that ministers decided.
The government has yet to decide how privatisation is to be achieved,
although Mr Heseltine indicated that financial support would be made
available so that management and employees could make a bid. Other bidders
might include rivals United Parcels Service, TNT, and Securicor.
Parcelforce has the leading 34 per cent share of ordinary parcel deliveries
but only two per cent of the premium 'next day' market. Its turnover for
1991-92 was Pounds 508m and it sustained a loss of Pounds 24m.
Mr Heseltine said Parcelforce was the only part of the Post Office that
would be affected, but the decision prompted speculation that it would be
followed by moves to privatise Royal Mail, the letters division.
The Conservative election manifesto said only that the party was committed
to maintaining a nationwide letter service with delivery to every address in
the UK with a uniform price structure.
Reaction from trade unions representing Parcelforce's 12,500 employees was
hostile, although Mr Terry Deegan, general secretary of the Communication
Managers' Association, said a management buyout 'might well be the least
undesirable privatisation option'.
The Union of Communication Workers, which represents most Parcelforce
workers, called for assurances on protection of the pension fund, job
security and continued union recognition. It also raised fears about the
future of rural parcel deliveries.
Sir Bryan Nicholson, Post Office chairman, said his board supported the
government's view that privatisation would 'provide the commercial framework
and access to capital that Parcelforce needs'. The operation would need
'continued significant investment' to secure a strong future, he said.
Labour accused the government of indulging in 'privatisation for
privatisation's sake', and warned that the move threatened to undermine more
than 100 years of a universal parcel service.
The parliamentary recess means that a government statement on the sell-off
of British Coal is now not likely until the autumn, David Lascelles writes.
The government had been hoping to clarify plans for a sell-off by this week
but negotiations on long-term coal supply contracts between British Coal and
the power generators remain unresolved.
</TEXT>
