<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / Environment agency given go-ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is to press ahead with a 'one-stop shop for environmental
protection', bringing together control of air, land and water pollution, Mr
Michael Howard, environment secretary, said yesterday.
An independent environment agency was proposed by the government last year.
The Queen's Speech two months ago, outlining the legislative programme after
the election, failed to mention it. This prompted speculation that the
agency had fallen victim to inter-departmental wrangles about river
regulation.
Since then, the Rio Summit and the UK's accession to the presidency of the
EC have given environmental matters a fresh prominence.
The bill needed to create the agency was 'a high priority', Mr Howard said,
although he added that there was unlikely to be parliamentary time for the
legislation in the next 12 months.
The agency will combine the functions of the National Rivers Authority, the
Inspectorate of Pollution and waste regulation by local authorities. In
drawing together the NRA and HMIP, one of the agency's most important
effects is likely to be an improvement in control of river pollution.
The agency would cover England and Wales, and the arrangements for Scotland
would be announced separately, he said.
Local authorities will continue to be responsible for controlling low-level
industrial air pollution.
There would be no changes in ministerial policy responsibilities, Mr Howard
said. Mr John Gummer, minister of agriculture, fisheries and food, will
continue to be responsible for coastal defences and land drainage.
The chosen structure of the environment agency was supported by the NRA, by
the water supply companies and by environmental groups for its decision to
leave the NRA in one piece.
It ends speculation about whether the agency would take over only the NRA's
pollution regulation role and split off its river management operations.
Mr Gummer said it was important the agency's main purpose should be clearly
perceived to be protection of the environment.
He said he had initially been concerned that the twin roles of the NRA would
blur this image. However, he was satisfied that the NRA would pursue
vigorously its policy of contracting out its river management.
</TEXT>
