<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / Parliament and Politics: TGWU chief in benefits call
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR'S traditional support for universal entitlement to welfare benefits
has come under pressure after unexpected support for targeted benefits from
Mr Bill Morris, leader of the TGWU general union, Britain's largest.
Mr Morris, whose union controls more than 10 per cent of the total vote at
Labour's policy-making annual conference, says in an article in the New
Statesman: 'I favour an examination of the ineffective system of universal
entitlements, perhaps looking at moving towards a more flexible programme
that offers individual pathways out of poverty.
'This does not mean a move away from equality. Instead, I see it as a move
towards genuine equality, an equality that does not pretend that the state
needs to offer the same to the two-income, two-car family as it offers to
the poor any more than men need the same protection as women, or white
people the same as black.'
Using the example of child benefit, he proposes a compromise of much lower
universal payments with additional payments for those in need, should the
party feel the need to continue to satisfy the principle of universality.
</TEXT>
