<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / Parliament and Politics: PM angered by revolt over MPs'
allowances
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DOWNING STREET yesterday made known the prime minister's anger at the
outcome of the Commons vote on MPs' allowances in the early hours that led
to a government defeat - the first of his premiership.
Mr Major watched as Conservative backbenchers defied ministerial pleas for
restraint in a vote giving MPs a 38 per cent increase office expenses -
Pounds 7,000 higher than the recommended figure.
The government feels the rebellion, costing some Pounds 8m, would send the
wrong signals to business and the public sector at a time when modest pay
increases were being sought to keep the downward pressure on inflation.
Some ministers, including Mr Major, are expected to forego the increases as
an example to their colleagues.
Coming in the wake of the prime minister's intervention last week to allow
top public servants only 4 per cent against the up to 24 per cent
recommended by a pay review body, the vote provoked grumbling among
Whitehall civil servants whose pay claims have been held down.
Officials said that Mr Major had made a point of being present for the vote
and regarded the government's proposal of a 14 per cent increase to Pounds
33,190 in MPs allowances as 'generous' in the prevailing economic climate.
Several Conservative MPs were unrepentant, however, claiming that the
increase now approved - taking total allowances from Pounds 28,986 to just
under Pounds 40,000 - was necessary to meet growing workloads.
They reiterated the point that the new money would meet the costs of hiring
equipment and staff and should not be confused with a salary rise.
However, several MPs admitted that some of the increase would be enjoyed by
their wives, who worked in the Commons as secretaries. Another countered
that the real impact of the increase would be felt as helping provide new
infrastructure and equipment for campaigning in constituencies.
'In effect, it is a state subsidy of the political parties by the backdoor,'
he said. 'I opposed the rise but I will have to take it or my opponents will
have the better of me.'
</TEXT>
