<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / Fears on N-plant safety: Nuclear watchdog questions Sizewell
B computer systems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY and DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NUCLEAR ELECTRIC has been asked to consider strengthening the back-up safety
system at Sizewell B, Britain's most advanced nuclear reactor, after fears
over the principal computer-controlled safety system.
The state-owned power generator, intended Sizewell B in Suffolk to be the
first UK nuclear power station to rely on a computer-controlled primary
system to detect faults and shut the reactor down if necessary. The station
is due for completion in 1994.
But the Nuclear Installations Inspectorate, part of the government's health
and safety executive, has asked Nuclear Electric to examine extending its
back-up system, which is not computer-controlled, so that it could also
carry out the functions of the main system.
Nuclear Electric said last night that the back-up system at Sizewell, which
will be the UK's first pressurised water reactor, operated on the same
principle as those used at existing nuclear stations. The
computer-controlled primary system was an additional safeguard aimed at
protecting against more remote risks.
The company said that human operators would be able to override the
computer-controlled system and shut down the plant at any stage if they
suspected a fault. The computer would prevent them only from taking action
that would compromise the plant's safety.
Today's Computer Weekly magazine reports that the inspectorate asked Nuclear
Electric to consider increasing the scope of its back-up safety system at a
meeting of the Advisory Committee on the Safety of Nuclear Installations at
Sizewell last month.
Nuclear Electric said yesterday that the costs of extending the secondary
safety system at Sizewell would be considerable. The costs have already
risen from Pounds 1.7bn to Pounds 2bn.
Nuclear Electric said the NII had said it would license the Sizewell B plant
without extending the secondary system if the company could substantiate the
validation tests it was performing on the computer-controlled system.
Radioactive waste should not pose a serious health risk to more than one
person in 100,000 per year, according to new objectives laid down by the
National Radiological Protection Board, David Lascelles writes.
The board also said that future generations should not be exposed to any
risks which would be considered unacceptable today.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
