<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / SFO tells of regrets over Blue Arrow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Serious Fraud Office would not handle the year-long Blue Arrow fraud
trial the same way again, the Court of Appeal heard yesterday.
Mr Nicholas Purnell QC, who brought the prosecution for the SFO, said his
original estimate that the trial would last four to six months was genuine
and sincere.
The first lesson to be learnt was that pre-trial hearings had to be more
rigorous than was the case in Blue Arrow, he said. However, there was no
risk that the convictions of four City advisers of conspiracy to defraud
were unsafe or unsatisfactory, he continued.
Mr Jonathan Cohen, Mr David Reed, Mr Nicholas Wells, all former County
NatWest executives, and Mr Martin Gibbs, a former UBS Phillips &amp; Drew
director, are appealing against their convictions for conspiracy to defraud.
In a separate hearing in the High Court Sir Nicholas Lyell, the
attorney-general, was given leave to bring a prosecution for contempt of
court against Associated Newspapers, publishers of the Mail on Sunday; Mr
Stewart Steven, the newspaper's former editor; and Mr Clive Wolman, City
editor.
Counsel for the attorney-general argued that the newspaper's publication of
interviews with members of the Blue Arrow jury constituted a breach of the
Contempt of Court Act 1981.
</TEXT>
