<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / Finance body warns on upturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FURTHER warning that the UK faces a slow economic recovery came yesterday
from the Finance and Leasing Association, whose members last year financed
more than 30 per cent of fixed investment.
The FLA said its latest economic survey showed that confidence about future
business conditions had declined since the general election.
The survey, carried out in June, found that 55 per cent of FLA members
polled expect confidence to increase over the next three months compared
with 83 per cent that expected an improvement immediately after the April
election.
'Post-election realism has set in and most companies now realise a recovery
will be slow,' said Mr Tony Mallin, deputy chairman of the FLA. However, he
added: 'Members have noticed some signs of revival in investment and
long-planned projects are now getting under way.'
The association said the most promising areas for investment activity
financed by leasing were in the small and middle ticket ranges. Some 70 per
cent of FLA members forecast an increase in leasing and hire purchase
agreements of up to Pounds 50,000 value over the next three months, while 51
per cent expected the demand for leases in the Pounds 50,000 to Pounds 1m
range to rise.
The FLA was founded this year to represent companies offering business
finance and leasing, consumer credit and motor finance. It expects its
members to have more than Pounds 30bn of new business this year.
</TEXT>
