<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / Radical accounts changes proposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PROFIT and loss account and balance sheet of many companies could be
fundamentally reshaped under radical proposals unveiled by the Accounting
Standards Board yesterday.
In two draft chapters in its 'statement of principles', the board makes
recommendations that could force all leases and off-balance-sheet finance
instruments to be included on the balance sheet.
It would also cast a shadow over the widespread practice of making large
provisions for reorganisation expenses on buying a company, which can then
be fed back to the profit and loss account.
'These go a long way beyond existing definitions,' said Mr David Tweedie,
chairman of the board. 'They are pretty fundamental and we expect an
onslaught of criticism.'
The impact of the draft chapters would be to improve the transparency of
accounts, and probably overall to increase companies' liabilities and allow
less room for them to massage profits.
The new chapters are the foundations on which new standards will be built.
The first chapter - the elements of financial statements - defines the basic
elements or items in accounts. It says that assets are 'rights or other
access to future economic benefits controlled by an entity as a result of
past transactions or events'. It stresses that they do not require
certainty, but only some possibility of access to future benefit.
Liabilities are 'an entity's obligations to transfer economic benefits as a
result of past transactions or events.'
The second chapter - covering the 'recognition' of these elements - says
that they should be incorporated into the accounts if they meet three
criteria: they meet the definitions; they can be measured reliably; and that
there is evidence of changes in assets or liabilities having occurred.
Organisations have until October 31 to comment on the discussion drafts.
The Elements of Financial Statements; The Recognition of Items in Financial
Statements, Accounting Standards Board, 100 Gray's Inn Road, London WC1X
8AL. Free
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
