<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / Maxwell probe challenge fails
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MARK HAAS, an executive director of Lehman Brothers International, the UK
arm of US investment bankers Lehman Brothers, has failed to block his
interrogation today about stock-lending agreements between Lehman and
Bishopsgate Investment Management.
The High Court yesterday rejected his challenge to an order under the
Insolvency Act that he submit to oral examination by the liquidators of BIM,
which managed Maxwell company pension schemes.
Mr Justice Hoffmann also rejected Mr Haas's plea that he be shown an
annexure to a confidential report by Mr Neil Cooper of Robson Rhodes, one of
the liquidators.
The annexure identified the informant who gave the liquidators information
about the agreements, which had suggested to them the line of inquiry they
wanted to pursue with Mr Haas, the judge said.
He said one of the agreements had involved Lehman lending BIM US Treasury
bills against collateral provided by BIM in the form of pension-fund
investments. The bills had immediately been converted into cash for BIM by
Lehman. On the face of it that arrangement, although designated as stock
lending, had been nothing more than a secured loan of money by Lehman to
BIM, the judge said.
Ruling that Mr Haas's interrogation must go ahead, the judge said the
liquidators were concerned to discover the extent of Lehman's knowledge of
the nature and purpose of the stock-lending agreements.
The primary purpose of the interrogation was to discover whether they had
grounds for suing Lehman.
Parliament, Page 10
