<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / Skill shortage expected to cloud upturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE recession has perman-ently changed companies' staffing patterns but as
the economy picks up businesses are still likely to be affected by skill
shortages, a survey of 350 companies by Reed Personnel Services found.
The changes identified include: more central control over staffing, the
restructuring and cross-training of a permanent core of staff, and greater
use of flexible contracts. More than 80 per cent of companies said they
wanted to hold on to these changes and would be able to do so.
The survey says that companies have learnt to do more with less staff, but
during the next six months 38 per cent of companies expect to take on
permanent staff and 26 per cent temporary staff.
A shortage of skilled staff will develop alongside continuing high
unemployment for both unskilled staff and managers. Only 11 per cent of
companies expect to take on more managers as the recession ends, but 33 per
cent expect to take on more skilled staff.
The number of skilled staff fell in only 20 per cent of companies as the
recession deepened. Personnel departments also survived the recession
relatively well, with staff cuts declining in only 17 per cent of companies.
Several reports have been published to coincide with today's announcement of
last month's unemployment figures which are expected to show another
substantial rise.
The Trades Union Congress said that on current trends employment will not
start growing until 1994 and the AEEU engineering and electrical union has
identified 22,500 manufacturing job losses since mid March, bringing the
total for the year to 55,000.
Recruitment consultant Alfred Marks says the number of permanent job
vacancies continues to grow slowly. In the past three months vacancies are
14 per cent up on the first three months of the year.
The number of employers offering paternity leave has nearly doubled over the
past three years, according to the largest survey of personnel management in
Europe by the Price Waterhouse Cranfield Project.
The survey found companies maintained equal opportunities policies in spite
of the recession.
</TEXT>
